{"title_page": "Hughes, Australian Capital Territory", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb \n| name     = Hughes\n| state    = act\n| city     = Canberra\n| image    = Hughes IBMap-MJC.png\n| caption  = \n| lga      = [[Woden Valley (district)|Woden Valley]]\n| postcode = 2605\n| est      = 1963\n| area     = 1.8\n| pop      = 2990\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census\">{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC80075|name=Hughes (State Suburb)|accessdate=30 June 2017|quick=on}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|-35.333|149.094|region:AU_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type = nomap\n| stategov = [[Murrumbidgee electorate|Murrumbidgee]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Canberra|Canberra]]\n| near-nw  = [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]\n| near-n   = [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]]\n| near-ne  = [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]]\n| near-e   = [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory|Red Hill]]\n| near-w   = [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]\n| near-sw  = [[Phillip, Australian Capital Territory|Phillip]]\n| near-s   = [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]]\n| near-se  = [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]]\n}}\n'''Hughes''' is a suburb in the [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] district of [[Woden Valley (district)|Woden]]. The postcode is 2605. The area of the suburb is 1.81&nbsp;km\u00b2.\n\n==History==\n\nHughes is named after [[Billy Hughes|The Right Honourable William Morris \"Billy\" Hughes]], seventh [[Prime Minister of Australia]] from 1915\u20131923.  Streets in the suburb are named with the theme of World War I armed services personnel and contemporaries of William Hughes.<ref name=name>{{cite web | url = http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/tools_resources/place_search3?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHAlM0ElMkYlMkYyMDMuOS4yNDkuMyUyRlBsYWNlTmFtZXMlMkZQbGFjZURldGFpbHMuYXNweCUzRm9iamVjdElEJTNENTM2MzMmYWxsPTE%3D | title = Suburb Name search results| publisher = ACT Environment and Sustainable Development| accessdate = 5 February 2014}}</ref>  The suburb was gazetted on 20 September 1962, with a population of nine. Residential construction began in 1963, and by 1974 Hughes had a population of 4050.\n\n==Geography==\n\nHughes adjoins the suburbs of [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]], [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]], [[Phillip, Australian Capital Territory|Phillip]] and [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]. It is bounded by Carruthers Street to the North, Yarra Glen and Yamba Drive to the west, and the [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory|Red Hill]] area of [[Canberra Nature Park]] to the east and south.\n\n===Geology===\nHughes has several different kinds of [[Geology of the Australian Capital Territory|rock]] from the [[Silurian]] period.  [[Shale]] from the [[Yarralumla, Australian Capital Territory|Yarralumla]] Formation is in the south west.  Cream coloured [[rhyolite]] from the Mount Painter Volcanics is found in the north west. Dark purple [[rhyodacite]] from the [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]] Volcanics is found in the north of Hughes.  In the south east [[tuff]] forms a layer on top of the Mount Painter Volcanics. An inactive north west - south east trending fault runs through the middle of the suburb.  Movement was down on the north east side.<ref>{{cite map|author1=Henderson, G. A. M.|author2=Matveev, G.|title=Geology of Canberra, Queanbeyan and Environs |scale=1:50000 |year=1980}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\nAt the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Hughes had a population of 2,990 people.<ref name=Census/>\n\n==Suburb amenities==\n\n===Shopping===\n\nA small shopping centre consists of a take-away restaurant, chemist/sub-newsagency, bakery/cafe, supermarket, post office,dry cleaner, hairdresser, real estate agent, and service station and mechanical workshop.\n\n===Recreation===\n\nSporting facilities are North Woden Tennis club<ref name=nplan>http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/2517/hughes-anp.pdf</ref> and Clarrie Hermes Park (Hughes Oval), as well as three local area playgrounds.\n\nWalking trails commence in the north-east of the suburb which run to the north of Federal Golf Course through to [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory#Canberra Nature Park: Red Hill|Red Hill Nature Reserve]].  Parts of the suburb have views over the Woden valley and the Woden town centre to the northern reaches of the [[Brindabella National Park|Brindabellas]].\n\n===Education===\n\nLocated in the suburb are Hughes primary school<ref>http://www.hughesps.act.edu.au/</ref> and Hughes pre-school.\n\n===Religion===\n\nThere are three Christian churches in Hughes: Jehovah's Witnesses, Canberra Christadelphians and the [[Baptist Church]]<ref>http://www.hughesbaptist.org/</ref>\n\n===Other===\n\nSt Andrews village is a retirement village, that was controversially built next to Yarra Glen, the highway bounding the west side of the suburb.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Woden Valley Suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Canberra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb \n| name     = Hughes\n| state    = act\n| city     = Canberra\n| image    = Hughes IBMap-MJC.png\n| caption  = \n| lga      = [[Woden Valley (district)|Woden Valley]]\n| postcode = 2605\n| est      = 1963\n| area     = 1.8\n| pop      = 2990\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census\">{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC80075|name=Hughes (State Suburb)|accessdate=30 June 2017|quick=on}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|-35.333|149.094|region:AU_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type = nomap\n| stategov = [[Murrumbidgee electorate|Murrumbidgee]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Canberra|Canberra]]\n| near-nw  = [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]\n| near-n   = [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]]\n| near-ne  = [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]]\n| near-e   = [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory|Red Hill]]\n| near-w   = [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]\n| near-sw  = [[Phillip, Australian Capital Territory|Phillip]]\n| near-s   = [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]]\n| near-se  = [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]]\n}}\n'''Hughes''' is a suburb in the [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] district of [[Woden Valley (district)|Woden]]. The postcode is 2605. The area of the suburb is 1.81&nbsp;km\u00b2.\n\n==History==\n\nHughes is named after [[Billy Hughes|The Right Honourable William Morris \"Billy\" Hughes]], seventh [[Prime Minister of Australia]] from 1915-1923.  Streets in the suburb are named with the theme of World War I armed services personnel and contemporaries of William Hughes.<ref name=name>{{cite web | url = http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/tools_resources/place_search3?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHAlM0ElMkYlMkYyMDMuOS4yNDkuMyUyRlBsYWNlTmFtZXMlMkZQbGFjZURldGFpbHMuYXNweCUzRm9iamVjdElEJTNENTM2MzMmYWxsPTE%3D | title = Suburb Name search results| publisher = ACT Environment and Sustainable Development| accessdate = 5 February 2014}}</ref>  The suburb was gazetted on 20 September 1962, with a population of nine. Residential construction began in 1963, and by 1974 Hughes had a population of 4050.\n\n==Geography==\n\nHughes adjoins the suburbs of [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]], [[Garran, Australian Capital Territory|Garran]], [[Phillip, Australian Capital Territory|Phillip]] and [[Curtin, Australian Capital Territory|Curtin]]. It is bounded by Carruthers Street to the North, Yarra Glen and Yamba Drive to the west, and the [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory|Red Hill]] area of [[Canberra Nature Park]] to the east and south.\n\n===Geology===\nHughes has several different kinds of [[Geology of the Australian Capital Territory|rock]] from the [[Silurian]] period.  [[Shale]] from the [[Yarralumla, Australian Capital Territory|Yarralumla]] Formation is in the south west.  Cream coloured [[rhyolite]] from the Mount Painter Volcanics is found in the north west. Dark purple [[rhyodacite]] from the [[Deakin, Australian Capital Territory|Deakin]] Volcanics is found in the north of Hughes.  In the south east [[tuff]] forms a layer on top of the Mount Painter Volcanics. An inactive north west - south east trending fault runs though the middle of the suburb.  Movement was down on the north east side.<ref>{{cite map|author1=Henderson, G. A. M.|author2=Matveev, G.|title=Geology of Canberra, Queanbeyan and Environs |scale=1:50000 |year=1980}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\nAt the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Hughes had a population of 2,990 people.<ref name=Census/>\n\n==Suburb amenities==\n\n===Shopping===\n\nA small shopping centre consists of a take-away restaurant, chemist/sub-newsagency, bakery/cafe, supermarket, post office,dry cleaner, hairdresser, real estate agent, and service station and mechanical workshop.\n\n===Recreation===\n\nSporting facilities are North Woden Tennis club<ref name=nplan>http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/2517/hughes-anp.pdf</ref> and Clarrie Hermes Park (Hughes Oval), as well as three local area playgrounds.\n\nWalking trails commence in the north-east of the suburb which run to the north of Federal Golf Course through to [[Red Hill, Australian Capital Territory#Canberra Nature Park: Red Hill|Red Hill Nature Reserve]].  Parts of the suburb have views over the Woden valley and the Woden town centre to the northern reaches of the [[Brindabella National Park|Brindabellas]].\n\n===Education===\n\nLocated in the suburb are Hughes primary school<ref>http://www.hughesps.act.edu.au/</ref> and Hughes pre-school.\n\n===Religion===\n\nThere are three Christian churches in Hughes: Jehovah's Witnesses, Canberra Christadelphians and the [[Baptist Church]]<ref>http://www.hughesbaptist.org/</ref>\n\n===Other===\n\nSt Andrews village is a retirement village, that was controversially built next to Yarra Glen, the highway bounding the west side of the suburb.\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Woden Valley Suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Canberra]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: runs though  \u2192  runs through,typo(s) fixed: 1915-1923 \u2192 1915\u20131923", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughes,_Australian_Capital_Territory"}
{"title_page": "2017 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 2017\n| team = Hawaii Rainbow Warriors\n| image= Hawaii Warriors logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150\n| conference = Mountain West Conference\n| division= West Division\n| short_conf = MW\n| record = 3\u20139\n| conf_record = 1\u20137\n| head_coach = [[Nick Rolovich]] \n| hc_year = 2nd\n| off_coach= Brian Smith\n| oc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme= [[Spread offense|Spread]]\n| def_coach = Legi Suiaunoa\n| dc_year = 1st\n| def_scheme = [[4\u20133 defense|4\u20133]]\n| mvp = [[Diocemy Saint Juste]]\n| stadium = [[Aloha Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 50,000)\n}}\n{{2017 Mountain West Conference football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team''' represented the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] in the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Rainbow Warriors played their home games at [[Aloha Stadium]] in [[Honolulu]]. They competed in the West Division of the [[Mountain West Conference]] and were led by second-year head coach [[Nick Rolovich]]. They finished the season 3\u20139, 1\u20137 in Mountain West play to finish in a tie for fifth place in the West Division. This marked the seventh straight losing season, continuing a school record, compiling a record of 29-62 since 2011.\n\n==Schedule==\nAlthough NCAA rules allow Hawaii to play a 13-game regular season,<ref>{{cite web |author1=NCAA |title=2017-18 NCAA Division I Manual |url=http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/D118.pdf |website=NCAAPublications.com |publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association |accessdate=2017-11-05 |page=312 |format=PDF |date=July 2017}}</ref> only 12 games were scheduled for Hawaii's 2017 season.\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2017\n| poll = [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] released prior to game\n| timezone = Hawaii\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date 