inbow Warriors football team''' represented the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] in the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Rainbow Warriors played their home games at [[Aloha Stadium]] in [[Honolulu]]. They competed in the West Division of the [[Mountain West Conference]] and were led by second-year head coach [[Nick Rolovich]]. They finished the season 3\u20139, 1\u20137 in Mountain West play to finish in a tie for fifth place in the West Division. This marked the seventh straight losing season, continuing a school record, compiling a record of 29-62 since 2011.\n\n==Schedule==\nAlthough NCAA rules allow Hawaii to play a 13-game regular season,<ref>{{cite web |author1=NCAA |title=2017-18 NCAA Division I Manual |url=http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/D118.pdf |website=NCAAPublications.com |publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association |accessdate=2017-11-05 |page=312 |format=PDF |date=July 2017}}</ref> only 12 games were scheduled for Hawaii's 2017 season.\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2017\n| poll = [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] released prior to game\n| timezone = Hawaii\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 26\n| time = 1:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[2017 UMass Minutemen football team|UMass]]\n| site_stadium = [[Warren McGuirk Alumni Stadium|McGuirk Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Amherst, Massachusetts|Amherst, MA]]\n| tv = [[Eleven Sports Network (United States)|ELVN]]/[[Spectrum Sports|SPEC]]\u2606\n| score = 38\u201335\n| attend = 12,145\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 2\n| time = 7:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[2017 Western Carolina Catamounts football team|Western Carolina]]\n| site_stadium = [[Aloha Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Honolulu|Honolulu, HI]]\n| tv = SPEC PPV\n| score = 41\u201318\n| attend = 25,472\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 9\n| time = 12:00 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| op