s. Located in the [[Middletown Valley]] that stretches between the [[Catoctin Mountain]]s on the east and [[South Mountain (Maryland and Pennsylvania)|South Mountain]] on the west, the town reportedly gained its name from its location midway between those ranges.\n\n==History==\nA young Lieutenant [[George Washington]], while surveying the South Mountain area, reported that the valley to the east was one of the most beautiful places he had ever seen. Later, as a Colonel in 1755, he was to accompany General Braddock on the old Indian Trail that ran through the valley on his way to Fort Cumberland.\n\nThe early German and English settlers started to arrive in the valley in the 1730s. Among them was Michael Jesserong, who paid \u00a366 for {{convert|50|acre|m2}}. He named his property Middletown and sold the first lots there in 1767, the date officially marked as that of the town\u2019s founding.\n\nThe history of Middletown is a mirror on the nation\u2019s development. Main Street spread to the west with construction of the National Pike through the town in 1806; the telegraph lines from Frederick to Hagerstown were routed through Middletown in 1854; and in 1896, car 11 of the Frederick Middletown Railway made its first run to Middletown. During the Civil War, both armies passed through the town to the battles of South Mountain and Antietam. In the aftermath of those battles, Middletown opened its churches and homes to care for the wounded.\n\nMiddletown preserves many historic structures indicative of its various periods of development and prosperity. The core of the old town, comprising the several blocks along West Main Street ([[U.S. Route 40 Alternate (Hagerstown\u2013Frederick, Maryland)|US Route 40 Alt]]) and South Church Street ([[Maryland Route 17|MD Route 17]]) contains several examples of [[Federal architecture|Federal]] and [[Greek Revival]] architecture, including the Zion Evangelical Lutheran Church (1859-1860) and Christ Reformed Church United Church of Christ (1818). With the coming of the [[Hagerstown and Frederick Railway]] in the 1890s, the town expanded to the east, where several examples of various Victorian-era styles can be seen, including [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne]], [[Gothic Revival]], and later examples of [[Colonial Revival]] styles. The economic prosperity experienced in the town during the first quarter of the twentieth century led to the alteration of older commercial structures and the construction of new ones in the first few blocks of Main Street, including the [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] styled Valley Savings Bank (today the Middletown Valley Bank). Many of these structures are registered in the [[Middletown Historic District (Middletown, Maryland)|Middletown Historic District]].\n\n==Geography==\nMiddletown is located at {{coord|39|26|28|N|77|32|38|W|type:city}} (39.441155, -77.543761).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|1.74|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-01-25}}</ref> [[Catoctin Creek (Maryland)|Catoctin Creek]] flows due south from approximately one mile west of town to several miles south of town.\n\nTo the east, Middletown borders [[Braddock Mountain]], named after the British general [[Edward Braddock]]. The mountain itself, along with its community, [[Braddock Heights, Maryland|Braddock Heights]], is often said to be the roost of the mythical [[Snallygaster]], a bird/dragon creature said to abduct livestock and people from the surrounding valley.\n\n[[File:2019-05-19 13 09 05 View west along U.S. Route 40 Alternate (Main Street) just west of Maryland State Route 17 (Church Street) in Middletown, Frederick County, Maryland.jpg|thumb|left|US 40 Alt westbound in central Middletown]]\n\n==Transportation==\nThe main method of travel to and from Middletown is by road, and there are two primary highways serving the town. [[U.S. Route 40 Alternate (Hagerstown\u2013Frederick, Maryland)|U.S. Route 40 Alternate]] follows Main Street through Middletown, and connects eastward to [[Interstate 70 in Maryland|Interstate 70]] near [[Frederick, Maryland|Frederick]] and westward to [[Boonsboro, Maryland|Boonsboro]]. [[Maryland Route 17]] follows Church Street through the town, extending northward to I-70 at [[Myersville, Maryland|Myersville]] and southward to [[U.S. Route 340 in Maryland|U.S. Route 340]] near [[Brunswick, Maryland|Brunswick]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 746\n|1880= 705\n|1890= 667\n|1900= 665\n|1910= 692\n|1920= 749\n|1930= 818\n|1940= 839\n|1950= 936\n|1960= 1036\n|1970= 1262\n|1980= 1748\n|1990= 1834\n|2000= 2668\n|2010= 4136\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=4688\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> of 2010, there were 4,136 people, 1,484 households, and 1,166 families living in the town. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2377.0|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,569 housing units at an average density of {{convert|901.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the town was 91.9% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 2.8% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 2.8% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.6% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.6% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 3.1% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,484 households of which 45.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 64.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.4% had a male householder with no wife present, and 21.4% were non-families. 18.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.79 and the average family size was 3.16.\n\nThe median age in the town was 39.6 years. 29.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 6.5% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 23.2% were from 25 to 44; 29.7% were from 45 to 64; and 10.6% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the town was 48.8% male and 51.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 2,668 people, 960 households, and 728 families living in the town. The [[population density]] was 1,577.3 people per square mile (609.5/km\u00b2). There were 981 housing units at an average density of 580.0 per square mile (224.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 96.89% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.46% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.07% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.34% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.22% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.01% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.82% of the population.\n\nThere were 960 households out of which 44.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 63.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 24.1% were non-families. 18.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.78 and the average family size was 3.21.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 32.0% under the age of 18, 5.4% from 18 to 24, 29.9% from 25 to 44, 21.7% from 45 to 64, and 11.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 91.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $67,266, and the median income for a family was $80,115. Males had a median income of $48,864 versus $31,602 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $25,759. About 1.8% of families and 3.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 2.1% of those under age 18 and 8.5% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Charlie Keller|Charlie \u201cKing Kong\u201d Keller]]: five-time [[Major League Baseball]] [[MLB All-Star Game|All-Star]] for [[New York Yankees]] and [[Detroit Tigers]], four-time [[World Series]] champion\n*[[Hal Keller]]: [[Major League Baseball]] player, vice president/general manager of [[Seattle Mariners]]\n*[[Amber Theoharis]]: reporter for [[MASN]]/[[Baltimore Orioles]], co-host [[NFL Network]]\n*[[Scott Devours]]: drummer with [[Roger Daltrey]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Middletown, Maryland}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Middletown (Maryland)}}\n* [http://www.middletown.md.us/ Official website]\n* [http://www.middletownlions.org/ Middletown Lions Club]\n\n{{Frederick County, Maryland}}\n{{DCMetroArea}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Towns in Frederick County, Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "ColinBear", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middletown,_Maryland"}
{"title_page": "John Bourne (artist)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = John Bourne\n| image         = Photo of John Bourne by Charles Thomson.jpg\n| imagesize     = 180 px\n| caption       = John Bourne\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date|1943}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      = [[Imperial College of Science and Technology]]\n| movement      = [[Stuckism]]\n| works         = ''Aeroplane'', ''Tea at the Albert Dock''\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n\n'''John Bourne''' (born  1943) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] artist and painter, living and working in [[Wales]], and a member of the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] art movement.<ref name=milner118>Milner, Frank, ed. ''The Stuckists Punk Victorian'', p.118, [[National Museums Liverpool]] 2004, {{ISBN|1-902700-27-9}}. [[Charles Thomson (artist)|Charles Thomson]]'s essay, \"A Stuckist on Stuckism\", pages 6&ndash;30, can be found online at [http://www.stuckism.com/Walker/AStuckistOnStuckism.html stuckism.com].</ref> He founded the Wrexham Stuckists group in 2001<ref name=groups>[http://www.stuckism.com/world.html#Wrexham \"Stuckism International: Stuckist Groups\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref> and has been exhibited in the group's shows since then, including ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]''.<ref name=stuckismbourne>[http://www.stuckism.com/Bourne/index.html \"John Bourne\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref> He has also taken part in [[Stuckist demonstrations]] against the [[Turner Prize]].<ref name=demos>[http://www.stuckism.com/clown2000.html \"Stuckist demos\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008. Click on link for individual years 2003 &ndash; 2006.</ref> The subject matter for his paintings, which are done in a simplified style, comes from his memories.<ref name=welshpaintings>[http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/gallery/JohnBourne/JBDetails.htm \"John W Bourne\"], welshpaintings.co.uk. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nJohn Bourne was born in [[Staffordshire]], [[England]], and spent much of his childhood in Northern Ireland; his father was a [[Methodist]] minister in the [[Yorkshire Dales]] and passionate about [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]]: Bourne says that his earliest memory, aged three, was of his father copying a Van Gogh painting.<ref name=walkerbourne>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/johnbourne.asp \"John Bourne\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007231727/http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/johnbourne.asp |date=7 October 2008 }}, [[Walker Art Gallery]], [[National Museums Liverpool]]. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n[[Image:John Bourne. Aeroplane.jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne. ''Aeroplane'']]  1964&ndash;68, Bourne gained a BSc in Physics at the [[University College of North Wales]], followed 1968&ndash;71 by an MPhil (Research on Solid State Theory) at the [[Imperial College of Science and Technology]] and [[H. C. \u00d8rsted Institute]], [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=milner118/>\n\nHe worked as a computer programmer, maths teacher and physics lecturer, until 1986, when \"I did a Gauguin but not in the South Seas. I walked out. It was tremendous.\"<ref name=milner118/> He has been a full-time artist ever since then. In 1990, he won first prize in the Mostyn Open 1 competition.<ref name=milner118/> In 1991, he staged a solo show at Theatr Clwyd, [[Mold, Flintshire|Mold]].<ref name=welshpaintings/> He has said that the increasing dominance of [[conceptual art]] proved obstructive to his own progress as a painter, and this came to a head in November 2001, when his work was rejected from a local exhibition: he began to despair of getting exposure.<ref name=bournepaint>Bourne, John. [http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/magazine/april2002/stuckists/index.htm \"Stuckism: Paint before concept\"], welshpaintings.com, April 2002. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\nHe recalled an article about the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] painting group which had appeared in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and responded to them: \"I liked the Stuckist Manifesto with its emphasis on painting and artistic integrity. It contained many new ideas and seemed to sum up my disquiet concerning the contemporary art world. Here was a radical, modern movement which championed painting. Some of the artists appeared a little rough and their work at times shocking, but this seemed an advantage if anything.\"<ref name=bournepaint/>\n\n[[Image:The Stuckists Punk Victorian 4.jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne's work (on the left) at ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]'', 2004.]]\nHe immediately founded the Wrexham group of the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] art movement, the first group in Wales,<ref name=groups/> along with Elfyn Jones, Neil Robertson and Geraint Dodd.<ref name=bournepaint/> In 2002, he was included in ''The First Stuckist International'' and subsequent shows at the [[Stuckism International Gallery]] in London, as well as ''Stuck in Wednesbury'' at the [[Wednesbury]] Museum and Art Gallery.<ref name=stuckismbourne/> In 2003, founded the Welsh Stuckism International Centre at his home.<ref>Milner, p.21</ref>  From 2003, he took part in [[Stuckist demonstrations]] against the [[Turner Prize]] at [[Tate Britain]].<ref name=demos/>\n\nIn 2004, he was one of the fourteen \"founder and featured\" artists in ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]'' held at the [[Walker Art Gallery]] for the [[Liverpool Biennial]].<ref>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/ \"The Stuckists Punk Victorian\"], [[Walker Art Gallery]], [[National Museums Liverpool]]. Retrieved 6 April 2008.</ref> Bourne was a co-curator,<ref name=stuckismbourne/> doing work at the museum to arrange the show.<ref>Sherwin, Brian. [http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2007/02/art-space-talk-paul-harvey.html \"Art Space Talk: Paul Harvey\"], myartspace.com, 5 February 2007. Retrieved 8 April 2008.<!--This is part of a site with editorial oversight, not a user post.--></ref> Philip Key of the ''[[Liverpool Daily Post]]'' commented on the exhibition: \"And they are not all lacking artistic skills. John Bourne of the Wrexham Stuckists&mdash;there are now groups all over the world&mdash;paints some well thought-out subdued portraits including the pleasing foursome in Tea at the Albert Dock.\"<ref>Key, Philip. [http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0300whatson/0500galleries/2004/10/01/the-stuckists-the-walker-50061-14706401/ \"The Stuckists, The Walker\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614125916/http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0300whatson/0500galleries/2004/10/01/the-stuckists-the-walker-50061-14706401/ |date=14 June 2011 }}, ''[[Liverpool Daily Post]]'', 1 October 2004. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Tate]] gallery director, Sir Nicholas Serota was dubbed the \"least likely visitor\" to the show,<ref>Wright, Michael. [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article994648.ece \"Culture: Agenda\"], ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', 18 January 2004. Retrieved 7 July 2008.</ref> which included a wall of work satirising the Tate and Serota himself, such as Stuckist co-founder [[Charles Thomson (artist)|Charles Thomson's]] painting, ''[[Sir Nicholas Serota Makes an Acquisitions Decision]]'',<ref>Taylor, John Russell. [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article487759.ece \"Lord have Mersey\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 29 September 2004. Retrieved 22 March 2008.</ref> he did visit, describing the work as \"lively\",<ref name=pia>Pia, Simon. \"Simon Pia's Diary: Now the Stuckists are on the move\", ''[[The Scotsman]]'', p.22, 22 September 2004. Retrieved from [http://www.newsuk.co.uk newsuk], 15 March 2008.</ref> and meeting Bourne and other artists (see photo). In 2005, Serota rejected the Stuckists' offer of a donation of 160 paintings from the Walker show, because \"We do not feel that the work is of sufficient quality in terms of accomplishment, innovation or originality of thought to warrant preservation in perpetuity in the national collection\".<ref name=rejects>Alberge, Dalya. [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1710820,00.html \"Tate rejects \u00a3500,000 gift from 'unoriginal' Stuckists\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 28 July 2005. Retrieved 1 February 2008.</ref> Six of Bourne's paintings were amongst the rejected work.<ref>[http://www.stuckism.com/Tate/TateDonation.xls \"Works offered as a donation and rejected by the Tate gallery\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\n[[Image:2005 Stuckist Turner demo (2).jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne (third from left) at the [[Stuckist demonstrations|Stuckist demonstration]] outside the [[Turner Prize]] in 2005 against [[Tate's purchase of The Upper Room]].]]\nA direct consequence of the rejection was a Stuckist media campaign led by Thomson over the [[Tate's purchase of The Upper Room|Tate's purchase]] of its trustee [[Chris Ofili]]'s work, ''The Upper Room''.<ref name=punks>O'Keeffe, Alice. [http://observer.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,6903,1664698,00.html \"How Ageing Art Punks Got Stuck into Tate's Serota\"], ''[[The Observer]]'', 11 December 2005. Retrieved 1 February 2008</ref> This included a [[Stuckist demonstrations#2005|demonstration]] about the purchase outside the [[Turner Prize]] at [[Tate Britain]] in December 2005, where Bourne handed a protest leaflet to Serota<ref name=turner2005>[http://www.stuckism.com/Tate/Tate05.html \"Turner Prize demo: Sir Nicholas Serota at the demo\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 13 July 2008.</ref>\u2014an event which Thomson considers to have precipitated Serota's angry defence of the purchase at the prize ceremony in the evening.<ref name=turner2005/><ref>Marr, Andrew. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2005/12/07/do0705.xml \"Notebook\" (2nd item)], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 December 2005. Retrieved 13 July 2008.</ref> In 2006 the [[Charity Commission]] censured the Tate and ruled that it had broken the law in making the purchase and similar trustee purchases during the previous 50 years.<ref name=higgins>Higgins, Charlotte. [http://arts.guardian.co.uk/news/story/0,,1823781,00.html \"How the Tate broke the law in buying a \u00a3600,000 Ofili work\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 July 2006. Retrieved 1 February 2008</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' called the verdict \"one of the most serious indictments of the running of one of the nation's major cultural institutions in living memory.\"<ref name=reynolds>Reynolds, Nigel. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/07/19/ntate19.xml \"Tate broke charity laws by buying art from its trustees\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 21 July 2006. Retrieved 22 April 2008.</ref>\n\nBourne curated a Wrexham Stuckists show at the [[Oswestry]] Heritage Centre, [[Shropshire]], in 2005.<ref name=stuckismbourne/> He was one of the artists in the ''Triumph of Stuckism'', a Stuckist painting exhibition which comprised part of [[Liverpool Biennial]]'s 2006 programme at [[Liverpool John Moores University]].<ref name=stuckismbourne/>\n\nHe lives with his wife in a red-brick terrace in rural Wales, and has two daughters living in London.<ref name=walkerbourne/>\n\n==Art==\n\n[[Image:John Bourne. Epsom Kitchen.jpg|thumb|John Bourne. ''Epsom Kitchen''.]]\nBourne is mostly self-taught.<ref name=welshpaintings/> He works in acrylic, oil and ink to produce images, where visual detail is simplified in order to depict memories of both recent life and his Northern Ireland childhood.<ref name=welshpaintings/> He said:\n{{cquote|I start with memories. You only remember what\u2019s relevant. I make loads of sketches from imagination.  I pin the sketches on the wall. I often look at a sketch for months or even years before I see a way to make it into a painting. It usually goes well at first but then I run into problems of composition. I have to make many changes. Sometimes it\u2019s years later that I find a way to finish it. I\u2019m trying to reveal something of a world beyond time and space.<ref name=milner118/>}}\nHe describes the genesis of his painting ''Aeroplane'' as a fear of low-flying aircraft and the experience of seeing an aeroplane\u2014which looked like a [[World War II]] [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster bomber]]\u2014coming towards him over the treetops one day.<ref name=milner118/> While doing the painting he adjusted the angles in it obsessively \"to get it just right\".<ref name=milner118/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:John Bourne. The Milk Float.jpg|''The Milk Float''\nImage:John Bourne. The Amateur.jpg|''The Amateur''.\nImage:John Bourne. Domestic Scene.jpg|''Domestic Scene''\nImage:John Bourne. Postgraduates.jpg|''Postgraduates''\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|John Bourne}}\n*[http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/gallery/JohnBourne/JB1.htm John Bourne on Welsh Paintings site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050419143615/http://freespace.virgin.net/john.bourne1/wrexhamstuckists/ Wrexham Stuckists]\n* [http://stuckismwales.co.uk/ Wrexham Stuckists and Stuckism in Wales]\n\n{{Stuckism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourne, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British painters]]\n[[Category:British male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century British painters]]\n[[Category:Stuckism]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:English contemporary artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = John Bourne\n| image         = Photo of John Bourne by Charles Thomson.jpg\n| imagesize     = 180 px\n| caption       = John Bourne\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date|1943}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      = [[Imperial College of Science and Technology]]\n| movement      = [[Stuckism]]\n| works         = ''Aeroplane'', ''Tea at the Albert Dock''\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n\n'''John Bourne''' (born  1943) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] artist and painter, living and working in [[Wales]], and a member of the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] art movement.<ref name=milner118>Milner, Frank, ed. ''The Stuckists Punk Victorian'', p.118, [[National Museums Liverpool]] 2004, {{ISBN|1-902700-27-9}}. [[Charles Thomson (artist)|Charles Thomson]]'s essay, \"A Stuckist on Stuckism\", pages 6&ndash;30, can be found online at [http://www.stuckism.com/Walker/AStuckistOnStuckism.html stuckism.com].</ref> He founded the Wrexham Stuckists group in 2001<ref name=groups>[http://www.stuckism.com/world.html#Wrexham \"Stuckism International: Stuckist Groups\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref> and has been exhibited in the group's shows since then, including ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]''.<ref name=stuckismbourne>[http://www.stuckism.com/Bourne/index.html \"John Bourne\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref> He has also taken part in [[Stuckist demonstrations]] against the [[Turner Prize]].<ref name=demos>[http://www.stuckism.com/clown2000.html \"Stuckist demos\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008. Click on link for individual years 2003 &ndash; 2006.</ref> The subject matter for his paintings, which are done in a simplified style, comes from his memories.<ref name=welshpaintings>[http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/gallery/JohnBourne/JBDetails.htm \"John W Bourne\"], welshpaintings.co.uk. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nJohn Bourne was born in [[Staffordshire]], [[England]], and spent much of his childhood in Northern Ireland; his father was a [[Methodist]] minister in the [[Yorkshire Dales]] and passionate about [[Vincent van Gogh|Van Gogh]]: Bourne says that his earliest memory, aged three, was of his father copying a Van Gogh painting.<ref name=walkerbourne>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/johnbourne.asp \"John Bourne\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007231727/http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/johnbourne.asp |date=7 October 2008 }}, [[Walker Art Gallery]], [[National Museums Liverpool]]. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n[[Image:John Bourne. Aeroplane.jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne. ''Aeroplane'']]  1964&ndash;68, Bourne gained a BSc in Physics at the [[University College of North Wales]], followed 1968&ndash;71 by an MPhil (Research on Solid State Theory) at the [[Imperial College of Science and Technology]] and [[H. C. \u00d8rsted Institute]], [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=milner118/>\n\nHe worked as a computer programmer, maths teacher and physics lecturer, until 1986, when \"I did a Gauguin but not in the South Seas. I walked out. It was tremendous.\"<ref name=milner118/> He has been a full-time artist ever since then. In 1990, he won first prize in the Mostyn Open 1 competition.<ref name=milner118/> In 1991, he staged a solo show at Theatr Clwyd, [[Mold]].<ref name=welshpaintings/> He has said that the increasing dominance of [[conceptual art]] proved obstructive to his own progress as a painter, and this came to a head in November 2001, when his work was rejected from a local exhibition: he began to despair of getting exposure.<ref name=bournepaint>Bourne, John. [http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/magazine/april2002/stuckists/index.htm \"Stuckism: Paint before concept\"], welshpaintings.com, April 2002. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\nHe recalled an article about the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] painting group which had appeared in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and responded to them: \"I liked the Stuckist Manifesto with its emphasis on painting and artistic integrity. It contained many new ideas and seemed to sum up my disquiet concerning the contemporary art world. Here was a radical, modern movement which championed painting. Some of the artists appeared a little rough and their work at times shocking, but this seemed an advantage if anything.\"<ref name=bournepaint/>\n\n[[Image:The Stuckists Punk Victorian 4.jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne's work (on the left) at ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]'', 2004.]]\nHe immediately founded the Wrexham group of the [[Stuckism|Stuckists]] art movement, the first group in Wales,<ref name=groups/> along with Elfyn Jones, Neil Robertson and Geraint Dodd.<ref name=bournepaint/> In 2002, he was included in ''The First Stuckist International'' and subsequent shows at the [[Stuckism International Gallery]] in London, as well as ''Stuck in Wednesbury'' at the [[Wednesbury]] Museum and Art Gallery.<ref name=stuckismbourne/> In 2003, founded the Welsh Stuckism International Centre at his home.<ref>Milner, p.21</ref>  From 2003, he took part in [[Stuckist demonstrations]] against the [[Turner Prize]] at [[Tate Britain]].<ref name=demos/>\n\nIn 2004, he was one of the fourteen \"founder and featured\" artists in ''[[The Stuckists Punk Victorian]]'' held at the [[Walker Art Gallery]] for the [[Liverpool Biennial]].<ref>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/exhibitions/stuckists/ \"The Stuckists Punk Victorian\"], [[Walker Art Gallery]], [[National Museums Liverpool]]. Retrieved 6 April 2008.</ref> Bourne was a co-curator,<ref name=stuckismbourne/> doing work at the museum to arrange the show.<ref>Sherwin, Brian. [http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2007/02/art-space-talk-paul-harvey.html \"Art Space Talk: Paul Harvey\"], myartspace.com, 5 February 2007. Retrieved 8 April 2008.<!--This is part of a site with editorial oversight, not a user post.--></ref> Philip Key of the ''[[Liverpool Daily Post]]'' commented on the exhibition: \"And they are not all lacking artistic skills. John Bourne of the Wrexham Stuckists&mdash;there are now groups all over the world&mdash;paints some well thought-out subdued portraits including the pleasing foursome in Tea at the Albert Dock.\"<ref>Key, Philip. [http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0300whatson/0500galleries/2004/10/01/the-stuckists-the-walker-50061-14706401/ \"The Stuckists, The Walker\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614125916/http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0300whatson/0500galleries/2004/10/01/the-stuckists-the-walker-50061-14706401/ |date=14 June 2011 }}, ''[[Liverpool Daily Post]]'', 1 October 2004. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Tate]] gallery director, Sir Nicholas Serota was dubbed the \"least likely visitor\" to the show,<ref>Wright, Michael. [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article994648.ece \"Culture: Agenda\"], ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', 18 January 2004. Retrieved 7 July 2008.</ref> which included a wall of work satirising the Tate and Serota himself, such as Stuckist co-founder [[Charles Thomson (artist)|Charles Thomson's]] painting, ''[[Sir Nicholas Serota Makes an Acquisitions Decision]]'',<ref>Taylor, John Russell. [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article487759.ece \"Lord have Mersey\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 29 September 2004. Retrieved 22 March 2008.</ref> he did visit, describing the work as \"lively\",<ref name=pia>Pia, Simon. \"Simon Pia's Diary: Now the Stuckists are on the move\", ''[[The Scotsman]]'', p.22, 22 September 2004. Retrieved from [http://www.newsuk.co.uk newsuk], 15 March 2008.</ref> and meeting Bourne and other artists (see photo). In 2005, Serota rejected the Stuckists' offer of a donation of 160 paintings from the Walker show, because \"We do not feel that the work is of sufficient quality in terms of accomplishment, innovation or originality of thought to warrant preservation in perpetuity in the national collection\".<ref name=rejects>Alberge, Dalya. [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1710820,00.html \"Tate rejects \u00a3500,000 gift from 'unoriginal' Stuckists\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 28 July 2005. Retrieved 1 February 2008.</ref> Six of Bourne's paintings were amongst the rejected work.<ref>[http://www.stuckism.com/Tate/TateDonation.xls \"Works offered as a donation and rejected by the Tate gallery\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 8 April 2008.</ref>\n\n[[Image:2005 Stuckist Turner demo (2).jpg|thumb|left|John Bourne (third from left) at the [[Stuckist demonstrations|Stuckist demonstration]] outside the [[Turner Prize]] in 2005 against [[Tate's purchase of The Upper Room]].]]\nA direct consequence of the rejection was a Stuckist media campaign led by Thomson over the [[Tate's purchase of The Upper Room|Tate's purchase]] of its trustee [[Chris Ofili]]'s work, ''The Upper Room''.<ref name=punks>O'Keeffe, Alice. [http://observer.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,6903,1664698,00.html \"How Ageing Art Punks Got Stuck into Tate's Serota\"], ''[[The Observer]]'', 11 December 2005. Retrieved 1 February 2008</ref> This included a [[Stuckist demonstrations#2005|demonstration]] about the purchase outside the [[Turner Prize]] at [[Tate Britain]] in December 2005, where Bourne handed a protest leaflet to Serota<ref name=turner2005>[http://www.stuckism.com/Tate/Tate05.html \"Turner Prize demo: Sir Nicholas Serota at the demo\"], stuckism.com. Retrieved 13 July 2008.</ref>\u2014an event which Thomson considers to have precipitated Serota's angry defence of the purchase at the prize ceremony in the evening.<ref name=turner2005/><ref>Marr, Andrew. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2005/12/07/do0705.xml \"Notebook\" (2nd item)], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 December 2005. Retrieved 13 July 2008.</ref> In 2006 the [[Charity Commission]] censured the Tate and ruled that it had broken the law in making the purchase and similar trustee purchases during the previous 50 years.<ref name=higgins>Higgins, Charlotte. [http://arts.guardian.co.uk/news/story/0,,1823781,00.html \"How the Tate broke the law in buying a \u00a3600,000 Ofili work\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 July 2006. Retrieved 1 February 2008</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' called the verdict \"one of the most serious indictments of the running of one of the nation's major cultural institutions in living memory.\"<ref name=reynolds>Reynolds, Nigel. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/07/19/ntate19.xml \"Tate broke charity laws by buying art from its trustees\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 21 July 2006. Retrieved 22 April 2008.</ref>\n\nBourne curated a Wrexham Stuckists show at the [[Oswestry]] Heritage Centre, [[Shropshire]], in 2005.<ref name=stuckismbourne/> He was one of the artists in the ''Triumph of Stuckism'', a Stuckist painting exhibition which comprised part of [[Liverpool Biennial]]'s 2006 programme at [[Liverpool John Moores University]].<ref name=stuckismbourne/>\n\nHe lives with his wife in a red-brick terrace in rural Wales, and has two daughters living in London.<ref name=walkerbourne/>\n\n==Art==\n\n[[Image:John Bourne. Epsom Kitchen.jpg|thumb|John Bourne. ''Epsom Kitchen''.]]\nBourne is mostly self-taught.<ref name=welshpaintings/> He works in acrylic, oil and ink to produce images, where visual detail is simplified in order to depict memories of both recent life and his Northern Ireland childhood.<ref name=welshpaintings/> He said:\n{{cquote|I start with memories. You only remember what\u2019s relevant. I make loads of sketches from imagination.  I pin the sketches on the wall. I often look at a sketch for months or even years before I see a way to make it into a painting. It usually goes well at first but then I run into problems of composition. I have to make many changes. Sometimes it\u2019s years later that I find a way to finish it. I\u2019m trying to reveal something of a world beyond time and space.<ref name=milner118/>}}\nHe describes the genesis of his painting ''Aeroplane'' as a fear of low-flying aircraft and the experience of seeing an aeroplane\u2014which looked like a [[World War II]] [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster bomber]]\u2014coming towards him over the treetops one day.<ref name=milner118/> While doing the painting he adjusted the angles in it obsessively \"to get it just right\".<ref name=milner118/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:John Bourne. The Milk Float.jpg|''The Milk Float''\nImage:John Bourne. The Amateur.jpg|''The Amateur''.\nImage:John Bourne. Domestic Scene.jpg|''Domestic Scene''\nImage:John Bourne. Postgraduates.jpg|''Postgraduates''\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|John Bourne}}\n*[http://www.welshpaintings.co.uk/gallery/JohnBourne/JB1.htm John Bourne on Welsh Paintings site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050419143615/http://freespace.virgin.net/john.bourne1/wrexhamstuckists/ Wrexham Stuckists]\n* [http://stuckismwales.co.uk/ Wrexham Stuckists and Stuckism in Wales]\n\n{{Stuckism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourne, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British painters]]\n[[Category:British male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century British painters]]\n[[Category:Stuckism]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:English contemporary artists]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:Fix placename links, replaced:Mold\u2192Mold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Bourne_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "The Economist", "text_new": "{{about||the profession|Economist|6=other uses|7=The Economist (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|English weekly news and international affairs publication}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Economist\n| logo = The Economist Logo.svg\n| image = 'The Economist' cover (September 8, 2001).png\n| caption = Cover of the 8 September 2001 issue{{#tag:ref|The title and its design are references to the book ''[[No Logo]]'' (1999).|group=\"nb\"}}\n| type = [[Weekly newspaper]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n| format = <!--The Economist is a newspaper printed in magazine format. Leave as \"magazine\" for format, with no hyperlink.-->Magazine\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1843|09}}\n| founder = [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]\n| owners = [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]]\n| ISSN = 0013-0613\n| political = <!--This is not an indiscriminate list, only the big, umbrella political camps The Economist belongs to.-->\n[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eb87e2f4-ffc9-11e9-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Liberalism at Large \u2014 how The Economist gets it right and spectacularly wrong|last=Zevin|first=Alexander|date=December 20, 2019|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Social liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Radical centrism]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-0|work=The Economist|title=Is The Economist left- or right-wing?|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21564556|work=The Economist|title=True Progressivism|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Adelphi, London|1-11 John Adam Street]]<br>[[City of Westminster|Westminster]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| editor = [[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]\n| website = {{url|economist.com}}\n| circulation = 909,476 (print)<br>748,459 (digital)<br>1.6 million (combined)\n| circulation_date = July-December 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=The Economist - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/432 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| logo_size = 135px\n| depeditor = [[Tom Standage]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Economist''''' is an international [[weekly newspaper]] <!--It is a newspaper NOT a magazine. Please see discussion at Talk:The Economist/Archive 2. The latter is \"printing format\" NOT a publication. Do not change wording without another editorial consensus on the talk as per WP:TITLE it is still a newspaper no matter how it is printed.-->printed in [[Magazine|magazine-format]] that focuses on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]], [[world news]], international business, and politics. Based in [[London|London, England]], the newspaper is owned by [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]], with core  editorial offices in major cities in North America, Europe, Asia, and the [[Middle East]]. In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million). In 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million. Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016. The newspaper has a prominent focus on [[data journalism]] and analysis over [[News media|original reporting]], to both criticism and acclaim.<!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Article uses British English, e.g. \"-ise\" over \"-ize\". See: WP:ISE.--><!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->\n\nFounded in 1843, ''The Economist'' was first circulated by Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] to muster support for abolishing the British [[Corn Laws]] (1815\u201346), a system of [[Tariff|import tariffs]]. Over time, the newspaper's coverage expanded further into [[political economy]] and eventually began running articles on current events, finance, commerce, and British politics. Throughout the mid- to late- 20th century, it greatly expanded its layout and format, adding [[Op-ed|opinion columns]], special reports, [[Political cartoon|political cartoons]], [[Letter to the editor|reader letters]], cover stories, art critique, book reviews, and technology features. The paper is often recognizable by its [[fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] nameplate and illustrated, topical covers. Individual articles are written anonymously, with [[Byline|no byline]], in order for the paper to speak as one collective voice. The paper is supplemented by its sister lifestyle magazine, ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]]'', and a variety of podcasts, films, and books.\n\nThe [[The Economist editorial stance|editorial stance of ''The Economist'']] primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]], [[Social liberalism|social]], and most notably, [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring policies and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper advocates for [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]]. Despite a pronounced editorial stance, it is seen as having little [[reporting bias]], rigorous [[Fact-checking|fact checking]] and strict [[copy editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/when-will-magazines-stop-trying-to-copy-the-economist|title=Why Time and Newsweek Will Never Be The Economist|last=Pressman|first=Matt|date=April 20, 2009|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/|title=10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts|last=Leadership|first=The Berlin School Of Creative|date=February 1, 2017|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Its extensive use of [[Word play|word play]], [[Subscription (finance)|subscription]] prices, and typical depth of coverage has linked the paper with a high-income and educated readership, drawing both positive and negative connotations in the [[Western world|Western World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/01/31/why-the-economist-swapped-its-famous-elitist-marketing-emotional-messaging|title=Why The Economist swapped its famous elitist marketing for emotional messaging|last=Burnell|first=Ian|date=31 January 2019|website=The Drum|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/09/business/media/09economist.html|title=The Economist Tends Its Sophisticate Garden|date=2010-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In line with this, it claims to have influential readership of prominent business leaders and [[Policy|policy-makers]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:James Wilson by Sir John Watson-Gordon.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] founded the newspaper to \"take part in a severe [[Debate|contest between intelligence]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reed.edu/reed-magazine/articles/2017/contest-letter-editor.html|title=The Contest|last=Lydgate|first=Chris|date=March 1, 2017|website=Reed Magazine|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2017}}</ref>|208x208px]]\n''The Economist'' was founded by the British businessman and banker [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] in 1843, to advance the repeal of the [[Corn Laws]], a system of import tariffs.<ref>[http://mitpress.typepad.com/mitpresslog/2007/01/from_corn_laws_.html From the Corn Laws to Your Mailbox], The MIT Press Log, 30 January 2007. Retrieved 11 June 2010.</ref> A [[prospectus (finance)|prospectus]] for the \"newspaper\" from 5 August 1843 enumerated thirteen areas of coverage that its editors wanted the publication to focus on:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=1873493|title=Prospectus|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=5 August 1843}}</ref>\n# Original [[editorial|leading articles]], in which free-trade principles will be most rigidly applied to all the important questions of the day.\n# Articles relating to some practical, commercial, agricultural, or foreign topic of passing interest, such as foreign treaties.\n# An article on the elementary principles of [[political economy]], applied to practical experience, covering the laws related to prices, wages, rent, exchange, revenue and taxes.\n# [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] reports, with particular focus on commerce, agriculture and free trade.\n# Reports and accounts of popular movements advocating free trade.\n# General news from the [[Court of St. James's]], the [[Greater London|Metropolis]], the [[Historic counties of England|Provinces]], Scotland, and Ireland.\n# Commercial topics such as changes in fiscal regulations, the state and prospects of the markets, imports and exports, foreign news, the state of the manufacturing districts, notices of important new mechanical improvements, shipping news, the money market, and the progress of railways and public companies.\n# Agricultural topics, including the application of geology and [[chemistry]]; notices of new and improved [[List of agricultural machinery|implements]], state of crops, markets, prices, foreign markets and prices converted into English money; from time to time, in some detail, the plans pursued in Belgium, Switzerland, and other well-cultivated countries.\n# [[British overseas territories|Colonial]] and foreign topics, including trade, produce, political and fiscal changes, and other matters, including [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9s]] on the evils of restriction and protection, and the advantages of free intercourse and trade.\n# Law reports, confined chiefly to areas important to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture.\n# Books, confined chiefly, but not so exclusively, to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture, and including all treatises on political economy, finance, or taxation.\n# A commercial [[gazette]], with prices and statistics of the week.\n# [[Letter to the editor|Correspondence and inquiries]] from the newspaper's readers.\n\nWilson described it as taking part in \"a severe contest between intelligence, which presses forward, and an unworthy, timid ignorance obstructing our progress\", a phrase which still appears on its masthead as the publication's mission.<ref name=\"opinion\">{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/ |title=Opinion: leaders and letters to the Editor |work=The Economist |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> It has long been respected as \"one of the most competent and subtle Western periodicals on public affairs\".<ref name=\"Leites\">{{cite journal|title=The Politburo Through Western Eyes|pages=159\u2013185|author=Nathan Leites|journal=[[World Politics]]|year=1952|volume=4|issue=2|jstor=2009044|doi=10.2307/2009044}}{{subscription required}}</ref> It was cited by [[Karl Marx]] in his formulation of socialist theory, because Marx felt the publication epitomised the interests of the bourgeoisie <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YauuCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA242&dq=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&pg=PA242#v=onepage&q=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&f=false|title=Karl Marx: His Life and Thought|last=McLellan|first=David|date=1 December 1973|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349155149|language=en}}</ref> He wrote: \"the London ''Economist'', the European organ of the aristocracy of finance, described most strikingly the attitude of this class.\"<ref>Karl Marx, ''The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte'', VI (1852)</ref> In 1915, revolutionary [[Vladimir Lenin]] referred to ''The Economist'' as a \"journal that speaks for British millionaires\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theeconomist/status/955168910852153344?lang=en|author=The Economist|website=twitter.com}}</ref> Additionally Lenin claimed that ''The Economist'' held a \"bourgeois-pacifist\" position and supported peace out of fear of [[revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1915/may/01c.htm|title=Bourgeois Philanthropists and Revolutionary Social-Democracy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:The Economist 2019 1 o.jpg|left|thumb|A panel of journalists and public policy leaders at ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s 2019 India Summit.<nowiki/>]]In 1920, the paper's circulation rose to 6,170.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} In 1934, it underwent its first major redesign. The current [[fire engine red]] nameplate was created by [[Reynolds Stone]] in 1959.<ref name=\"About us\" /> In January 2012, ''The Economist'' launched a new weekly section devoted exclusively to China, the first new country section since the introduction of one on the United States in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economist Launches New China Section|url=http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|work=Asian Media Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201210032/http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|archivedate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 1991, [[James Fallows]] argued in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that ''The Economist'' used editorial lines that contradicted the news stories they purported to highlight.<ref name=\"fallows\" /> In 1999, [[Andrew Sullivan]] complained in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that it uses \"marketing genius\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/london-fog|title=London Fog|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> to make up for deficiencies in original reporting, resulting in \"a kind of ''[[Reader's Digest]]''\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3874750,00.html|title=Not so groovy.|date=14 June 1999|work=The New Republic|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref> for America's corporate elite.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Finkel|first=Rebecca|date=July 1999|title=Nasty barbs fly between New Republic and Economist|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/news1999/july99/news4707.html|magazine=Media Life|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107024913/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news1999/july99/news4707.html|archivedate=7 November 2015|accessdate=27 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"its writers rarely see a political or economic problem that cannot be solved by the trusted three-card trick of privatisation, deregulation and liberalisation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Stern|first=Stefan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/aug/21/pressandpublishing.business1|title=Economist thrives on female intuition|date=21 August 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 January 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' named it the best English-language paper noting its strength in international reporting where it does not feel moved to cover a faraway land only at a time of unmitigated disaster\" and that it kept a wall between its reporting and its more conservative editorial policies.<ref>Entertainment: 50 Best Magazines, Chicago Tribune, 15 June 2006.</ref> In 2008, [[Jon Meacham]], former editor of ''Newsweek'' and a self-described \"fan\", criticised ''The Economist''{{'s}} focus on analysis over original reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/node/39374|title=Jon Meacham Wants Newsweek to Be More Like Hayes' Esquire|work=The New York Observer|accessdate=27 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522125448/http://www.observer.com/node/39374|archive-date=22 May 2008}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Economist'' was [[2012 ICT Skype controversy|accused]] of hacking into the computer of Justice [[Mohammed Nizamul Huq]] of the [[Bangladesh]] Supreme Court, leading to his resignation as the chairman of the [[International Crimes Tribunal (Bangladesh)|International Crimes Tribunal]].<ref name=\"ICTleaks\">{{cite magazine|date=8 December 2012|title=Discrepancy in Dhaka|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/12/bangladesh|magazine=The Economist}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/bangladesh-crimes-tribunal-accuses-the-economist-magazine-of-hacking-judges-computer/2012/12/09/8f248da2-421e-11e2-8c8f-fbebf7ccab4e_story.html|title=Economist accused of hacking ICT judge's computer|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks2\">{{cite news|last=Hossain|first=Farid|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121209/as-bangladesh-war-crimes|title=Economist magazine faces contempt in Bangladesh|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/bangladeshi-war-crimes-tribunal-issues-notice-to-the-economist/1041394|title=Bangladeshi war crimes tribunal issues notice to The Economist|date=6 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-economist-pearson_55cb31f0e4b0923c12beac28?ir=Business&section=business&kvcommref=mostpopular|title=Pearson Unloads $731 Million Stake in the Economist|date=12 August 2015|work=HuffPost|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Shareholders ===\n[[File:Economist building London1.jpg|thumb|The Economist Building, until 2017, in [[London]], England on [[St James's Street]].|alt=]][[Pearson plc]] held a 50% shareholding via [[Financial Times|The Financial Times Limited]] until August 2015. At that time, Pearson sold their share in the Economist. The [[Agnelli family]]'s [[Exor (company)|Exor]] paid \u00a3287m to raise their stake from 4.7% to 43.4% while the Economist paid \u00a3182m for the balance of 5.04m shares which will be distributed to current shareholders.<ref name=\"West\">{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref> Aside from the Agnelli family, smaller shareholders in the company include [[Cadbury family|Cadbury]], [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]] (21%), [[Schroders|Schroder]], [[Baron Layton|Layton]] and other family interests as well as a number of staff and former staff shareholders.<ref name=\"West\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/agnellis-rothschilds-close-in-on-economist-magazine-sale-pearson/|title=Agnellis, Rothschilds close in on Economist|date=11 August 2015|work=POLITICO|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Trustee|board of trustees]] formally appoints the editor, who cannot be removed without its permission. Although ''The Economist'' has a global emphasis and scope, about two-thirds of the 75 staff journalists are based in the London borough of [[City of Westminster|Westminster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/so-whats-the-secret-of-the-economist-347699.html|title=So what's the secret of 'The Economist'?|date=26 February 2006|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Editor ===\n[[File:Zanny Minton Beddoes World Economic Forum 2013 cropped.jpg|thumb|254x254px|[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]] was appointed editor in 2015, first joining as an [[emerging markets]] correspondent in 1994.]]\nThe [[editor-in-chief]], commonly known simply as \"the Editor\", of ''The Economist'' is charged with formulating the paper's editorial policies and overseeing corporate operations. Since its 1843 founding, the editors have been:\n\n*[[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]: 1843\u20131857\n*[[Richard Holt Hutton]]: 1857\u20131861<ref>The ''Concise Dictionary of National Biography'' makes him assistant editor 1858\u20131860</ref>\n*[[Walter Bagehot]]: 1861\u20131877<ref>He was Wilson's son-in-law</ref>\n*[[Daniel Conner Lathbury]]: 1877\u20131881<ref>[[s:The Times/1922/Obituary/Daniel Conner Lathbury|A journalist and biographer]]</ref> (''jointly'')\n*[[Robert Harry Inglis Palgrave]]: 1877\u20131883 (''jointly'')\n* Edward Johnstone: 1883\u20131907<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|title=economist150\u5468\u5e74\uff081993\uff09 \u2013 \u7ecf\u6d4e\u5b66\u4eba\u8d44\u6599\u5e93 \u2013 ECO\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51 \u2013 Powered by Discuz! Archiver|author=Discuz! Team and Comsenz UI Team|accessdate=29 June 2015|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922170122/http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Francis Wrigley Hirst]]: 1907\u20131916\n* Hartley Withers: 1916\u20131921\n*[[Walter Layton, 1st Baron Layton|Sir Walter Layton]]: 1922\u20131938\n*[[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]]: 1938\u20131956\n*[[Donald Tyerman]]: 1956\u20131965\n*[[Alastair Burnet|Sir Alastair Burnet]]: 1965\u20131974\n*[[Andrew Knight (journalist)|Andrew Knight]]: 1974\u20131986\n*[[Rupert Pennant-Rea]]: 1986\u20131993\n*[[Bill Emmott]]: 1993\u20132006\n*[[John Micklethwait]]: 2006\u20132014<ref>{{cite news|title=John Micklethwait leaving the Economist to join Bloomberg News|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/09/john-micklethwait-leaving-economist-joining-bloomberg|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 December 2014|last1=Sweney|first1=Mark}}</ref>\n*[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]: 2015\u2013present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/zanny-minton-beddoes/|title=Zanny Minton Beddoes|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Tone and voice==\nThough it has many individual columns, by tradition and current practice the newspaper ensures a uniform voice\u2014aided by the anonymity of writers\u2014throughout its pages,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/styleguide/introduction|title=Style Guide | accessdate=8 February 2013|work=The Economist|date=27 September 2011}}</ref> as if most articles were written by a single author, which may be perceived to display dry, understated wit, and precise use of language.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/research/styleGuide/index.cfm?page=673927|title=The Economist \u2013 Tone|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |title=Johnson |accessdate=27 December 2006 |work=The Economist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219221031/http://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |archivedate=19 December 2006 }}</ref> <!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->''The Economist'' has traditionally\u2014albeit not always consistently\u2014persisted in referring to itself as a \"[[newspaper]]\", rather than a \"[[news magazine]]\", due to [[Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|its legal classification as a newspaper]] in Britain, its transition from [[broadsheet]] to glossy colour format, and its general focus on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] as opposed to specialist subjects.<ref name=\"pgazette\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist''{{'}}s treatment of economics presumes a working familiarity with fundamental concepts of classical economics. For instance, it does not explain terms like [[invisible hand]], [[macroeconomics]], or [[demand curve]], and may take just six or seven words to explain the theory of [[comparative advantage]]. Articles involving economics do not presume any formal training on the part of the reader and aim to be accessible to the educated layman. It usually does not translate short French (and German) quotes or phrases. It does describe the business or nature of even well-known entities, writing, for example, \"[[Goldman Sachs]], an investment bank\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2008/02/21/a-bank-by-any-other-name|title=A bank by any other name|date=2008-02-21|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' is known for its extensive use of [[word play]], including puns, allusions, and metaphors, as well as alliteration and assonance, especially in its headlines and captions. This can make it difficult to understand for those who are not native English speakers.<ref>Richard J. Alexander, \"Article Headlines in ''The Economist'': An Analysis of Puns, Allusions and Metaphors\", ''Arbeiten aus Anglistik und Amerikanistik '''11''':2:159-177 (1986) {{jstor|43023400}}''</ref>\n\n===Editorial anonymity===\n[[File:The Economist Article.jpg|thumb|''Economist'' articles typically do not carry [[Byline|bylines]], anonymously publishing their work. |211x211px]]\nArticles often take a definite editorial stance and almost never carry a [[byline]]. Not even the name of the editor is printed in the issue. It is a long-standing tradition that an editor's only signed article during their tenure is written on the occasion of their departure from the position. The author of a piece is named in certain circumstances: when notable persons are invited to contribute opinion pieces; when journalists of ''The Economist'' compile special reports (previously known as surveys); for the Year in Review special edition; and to highlight a potential [[conflict of interest]] over a book review. The names of ''The Economist'' editors and correspondents can be located on the media directory pages of the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory|title=Media directory|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Online blog pieces are signed with the initials of the writer and authors of print stories are allowed to note their authorship from their personal web sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://andreaskluth.org/2008/11/20/why-the-economist-has-no-bylines/|title=Why The Economist has no bylines |work=Andreaskluth.org|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=20 November 2008 }}</ref> \"This approach is not without its faults (we have four staff members with the initials \"J.P.\", for example) but is the best compromise between total anonymity and full bylines, in our view\", wrote one anonymous writer of The Economist.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-1/|title=Why are The Economist's writers anonymous? |journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 September 2016|date=4 September 2013 }}</ref> There are three editorial and business areas in which the anonymous ethos of the weekly has contributed to strengthening its unique identity: collective and consistent voice, talent and newsroom management, and brand strength and clarity. <ref>{{cite journal |last=Arrese |first=\u00c1ngel |title=\"\u201cIt\u2019s Anonymous. It\u2019s The Economist\u201d. The Journalistic and Business Value of Anonymity\" |journal=Journalism Practice |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2020.1735489}}</ref>\n\nThe editors say this is necessary because \"collective voice and personality matter more than the identities of individual journalists\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/help/about-us|title=The Economist \u2013 About us|accessdate=11 June 2012|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> and reflects \"a collaborative effort\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|title=Economist Editor Micklethwait brings his global perspective to the Twin Cities|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=29 April 2008|publisher=MinnPost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705161308/http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|archive-date=5 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In most articles, authors refer to themselves as \"your correspondent\" or \"this reviewer\". The writers of the titled opinion columns tend to refer to themselves by the title (hence, a sentence in the \"Lexington\" column might read \"Lexington was informed...\").\n\nAmerican author and long-time reader [[Michael Lewis (author)|Michael Lewis]] criticised the paper's editorial anonymity in 1991, labelling it a means to hide the youth and inexperience of those writing articles.<ref name=\"fallows\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/1991/10/-quot-the-economics-of-the-colonial-cringe-quot-about-the-economist-magazine-washington-post-1991/7415/|title=The Economics of the Colonial Cringe: Pseudonomics and the Sneer on the Face of The Economist.|accessdate=27 April 2008|work=The Washington Post|date=16 October 1991}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2019/07/01/bestselling-author-michael-lewis-has-it-all-figured-out/|title=Bestselling Author Michael Lewis Has It All Figured Out|last=High|first=Peter|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Although individual articles are written anonymously, there is no secrecy over who the writers are as they are listed on ''The Economist''{{'s}} website, which also provides summaries of their careers and academic qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media directory|url=http://mediadirectory.economist.com/|work=The Economist|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Later, in 2009, Lewis included multiple ''Economist'' articles in his [[anthology]] about the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], ''[[Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lewis|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Panic.html?id=ZXUOASHVf_YC|title=Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity|date=2009|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-06514-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[John Ralston Saul]] describes ''The Economist'' as a \"...[newspaper] which hides the names of the journalists who write its articles in order to create the illusion that they dispense disinterested truth rather than opinion. This sales technique, reminiscent of pre-Reformation Catholicism, is not surprising in a publication named after the social science most given to wild guesses and imaginary facts presented in the guise of inevitability and exactitude. That it is the Bible of the corporate executive indicates to what extent received wisdom is the daily bread of a managerial civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Doubter's Companion: A Dictionary of Aggressive Common Sense |id={{ASIN|0743236602|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n[[File:A stack of Economist papers.jpg|thumb|A stack of ''Economist'' papers, ordered by publication date. ''Pictured'': the 14 October 2019 issue. ]]\n''The Economist''{{'}}s primary focus is world events, politics and business, but it also runs regular sections on science and technology as well as books and the arts. Approximately every two weeks, the publication includes an in-depth special report<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/printedition/specialreports |title=Special reports |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> (previously called [[survey article|surveys]]) on a given topic. The five main categories are Countries and Regions, Business, Finance and Economics, Science and Technology, and Other. Every three months, it publishes a technology report called ''Technology Quarterly''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/science/tq/ |title=Technology Quarterly |work=The Economist |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> or TQ, a special section focusing on recent trends and developments in science and technology.\n\nSince July 2007, there has also been a complete audio edition of the paper available 9&nbsp;pm London time on Thursdays.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Katie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/11/pressandpublishing.business1 |title=Economist launches audio magazine|work=The Guardian|location=London |date=11 July 2007 |accessdate=21 September 2016 }}</ref> The audio version of ''The Economist'' is produced by the production company ''Talking Issues''. The company records the full text of the newspaper in [[MP3]] format, including the extra pages in the UK edition. The weekly 130 MB download is free for subscribers and available for a fee for non-subscribers.\n\nThe publication's writers adopt a tight style that seeks to include the maximum amount of information in a limited space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/StyleGuide/|title=The Economist style guide|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist }}</ref> [[David G. Bradley]], publisher of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', described the formula as \"a consistent world view expressed, consistently, in tight and engaging prose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp|title=A Seven Year Ambition|work=mediabistro.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010200210/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp |archivedate=10 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Letters===\n''The Economist'' frequently receives letters from senior businesspeople, politicians, ambassadors, and from spokespeople for various government departments, non-governmental organisations and lobbies. Well-written or witty responses from anyone are considered, and controversial issues frequently produce a torrent of letters. For example, the survey of [[corporate social responsibility]], published January 2005, produced largely critical letters from [[Oxfam]], the [[World Food Programme]], [[United Nations Global Compact]], the Chairman of [[BT Group]], an ex-Director of [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] and the UK [[Institute of Directors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-humanrights.org/Links/Repository/542754|title=Compilation: Full text of responses to Economist survey on Corporate Social Responsibility (January\u2013February 2005)|work=Business & Human Rights|accessdate=3 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nMany of the letters published are critical of its stance or commentary. After ''The Economist'' ran a critique of [[Amnesty International]] and human rights in general in its issue dated 24 March 2007, its letters page ran a reply from Amnesty, as well as several other letters in support of the organisation, including one from the head of the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=8954694|title=Letters: On Amnesty International and human rights, Iraq, tax breaks 4&nbsp;April 2007|date=4 April 2007|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 November 2007}}</ref> Rebuttals from officials within regimes such as the Singapore government are routinely printed, to comply with local [[right-of-reply]] laws without compromising editorial independence.<ref>{{cite book|author=Francis T. Seow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CnZjYJ3TduUC&pg=PA173|title=The Media Enthralled: Singapore Revisited|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|year=1998|isbn=9781555877798|pages=171\u2013175|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is extremely rare for any comment by ''The Economist'' to appear alongside any published letter. Letters published in the paper are typically between 150 and 200 words long (and began with the salutation \"Sir\" until the editorship of Zanny Minton Beddoes, the first female editor; they now have no salutation). Previous to a change in procedure, all responses to on-line articles were usually published in \"The Inbox\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/debate/theinbox/|title=Latest blog posts|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> Comments can now be made directly under each article.\n\n=== Columns ===\n[[File:Economist Cartoon.jpg|thumb|A [[political cartoon]] published by the newspaper in November 2010, depicting  the [[European debt crisis|2010 European sovereign debt crisis]].|alt=|253x253px]]\nThe publication runs several opinion columns whose names reflect their topic:<!--Bolded because these columns redirect here, per WP:BOLD.-->\n\n*'''''Babbage''''' (Technology): named for the inventor [[Charles Babbage]], this column was established in March 2010 and focuses on various technology related issues.\n*'''''Bagehot''''' (Britain): named for [[Walter Bagehot]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|t\n}}), 19th-century British constitutional expert and early editor of ''The Economist''. Since April 2017 it has been written by [[Adrian Wooldridge]], who succeeded [[David Rennie (columnist)|David Rennie]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Britain's cheering gloom|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21557752 |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlemagne moves town|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/charlemagne/2010/06/charlemagne_moves_town |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''Banyan''''' (Asia): named for the [[banyan]] tree, this column was established in April 2009 and focuses on various issues across the Asian continent, and is written by [[Dominic Ziegler]].\n*'''''Baobab''''' (Africa & Middle East): named for the [[baobab]] tree, this column was established in July 2010 and focuses on various issues across the African continent.\n*'''''Bartleby''''' (Work and management): named after [[Bartleby|the titular character]] of a [[Herman Melville]] short story, this column was established in May 2018. It is written by [[Philip Coggan]].\n*'''''Bello''''' (Latin America): named for [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], a Venezuelan diplomat, poet, legislator and philosopher, who lived and worked in Chile.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Bello column: Choosing a Name|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/01/bello-column|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 March 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref> The column was established in January 2014 and is written by [[Michael Reid (journalist and writer)|Michael Reid]].\n*'''''Buttonwood''''' (Finance): named for the [[Platanus occidentalis|buttonwood]] tree where early [[Wall Street]] traders gathered. Until September 2006 this was available only as an on-line column, but it is now included in the print edition. Since 2018, it is written by John O'Sullivan, succeeding Philip Coggan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/john-osullivan/|title=John O'Sullivan|website=Economist|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n*'''''Chaguan''''' (China): named for Chaguan, the traditional Chinese Tea houses in [[Chengdu]], this column was established on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/09/13/the-economists-new-china-column-chaguan|publisher=The Economist website|title=The Economist's new China column: Chaguan|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n*'''''Charlemagne''''' (Europe): named for [[Charlemagne]], Emperor of the [[Francia|Frankish Empire]]. It is written by Jeremy Cliffe<ref>[http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ People: Jeremy Cliffe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075703/http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ |date=15 January 2019 }}{{snd}} Economist Media Directory. Retrieved 14/1/19</ref> and earlier it was written by David Rennie (2007\u20132010) and by Anton La Guardia<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Directory|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/anton-la-guardia|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 June 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> (2010\u20132014).\n\n*'''''Erasmus''''' (Religion and public policy) \u2013 named after the Dutch [[Christian humanist]] [[Erasmus]].\n*'''''Game Theory''''' (Sport): named after [[Game theory|the science of predicting outcomes]] in a certain situation, this column focuses on \"sports major and minor\" and \"the politics, economics, science and statistics of the games we play and watch\".\n*'''''Johnson''''' (language): named for [[Samuel Johnson]], this column returned to the publication in 2016 and covers language. It is written by [[Robert Lane Greene]].\n*'''''Lexington''''' (United States): named for [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the site of the beginning of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. From June 2010 until May 2012 it was written by [[Peter David (journalist)|Peter David]], until his death in a car accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/lexington/2012/05/lexington|publisher=The Economist website|title=Lexington: Peter David|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''''Prospero''''' (Books and arts): named after the character from [[William Shakespeare's]] play ''[[The Tempest]]'', this column reviews books and focuses on arts-related issues.\n*'''''Schumpeter''''' (Business): named for the economist [[Joseph Schumpeter]], this column was established in September 2009 and is written by Patrick Foulis.\n\n*'''''Free Exchange''''' (Economics): a general economics column, frequently based on academic research, replaced the column ''Economics Focus'' in January 2012\n*'''Obituary''' (recent death): Since 1997 it has been written by [[Ann Wroe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|title=An Interview with Ann Wroe, Obituaries Writer for The Economist|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223130322/http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|archive-date=23 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper goes to press on Thursdays, between 6&nbsp;pm and 7&nbsp;pm GMT, and is available at newsagents in many countries the next day. It is printed at seven sites around the world. Known on their website as \"This week's print edition\", it is available online, albeit with only the first five viewed articles being free (and available to subscribers only mid-October 2009 \u2013 2010). ''The Economist'' also produces the annual ''The World in'' [''Year''] publication.\n===Innovation Awards===\n[[File:Dimitris Droutsas at The Economist conference.jpg|thumb|293x293px|Greek Foreign Minister [[Dimitrios Droutsas|Dimitris Droutsas]] speaking at 2011 Economist Conference. ]]\n''The Economist'' sponsors the yearly \"Economist Innovation Awards\", in the categories of bioscience, computing and communications, energy and the environment, social and economic innovation, business-process innovation, consumer products, and a special \"no boundaries\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|title=Economist Innovation Awards Categories|publisher=The Economist Group|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117061347/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref> The awards have been held since 2002. Nominations are held between 2 and 30 April. The award ceremony is then hosted on 15 November. Choices are based on the following factors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|title=Economist Innovation Awards Nomination Process|publisher=Economistconferences.co.uk|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507204053/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n* How much revenue their innovation has made their company or its economic impact on a specific good cause or society in general\n* The effect their work has had on the marketplace (or if it's created a whole new marketplace altogether)\n* The impact their innovation has had on a new type of science or technology\n\n===Writing competitions===\n''The Economist'' sponsors a wide-array of writing competitions and prices throughout the year for readers. In 1999, ''The Economist'' organised a global futurist writing competition, [[The World in 2050]]. Co-sponsored by [[Royal Dutch/Shell]], the competition included a first prize of [[United States dollar|US$]]20,000 and publication in ''The Economist''{{'}}s annual flagship publication, ''The World In''.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=20000422&id=01ZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2003,2039685 | title=What is your vision of the future? | work=New Straights Times | date=22 April 2000}}</ref> Over 3,000 entries from around the world were submitted via a website set up for the purpose and at various Royal Dutch Shell offices worldwide.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\" /> The judging panel included [[Bill Emmott]], [[Esther Dyson]], Sir [[Mark Moody-Stuart]], and [[Matt Ridley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Getting better all the time |url=https://www.economist.com/node/16103826|work=The Economist |date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2019, they launched the Open Future writing competition with an inaugural youth essay-writing prompt about [[Global warming|climate change]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sefs.uw.edu/students/student-blog-post/climate-change-essay-contest-offered-by-the-economist/|title=Climate Change Essay Contest offered by The Economist|website=School of Environmental and Forest Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During this competition the paper accepted a submission from an [[Artificial intelligence|artificially-intelligent]] computer writing program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/10/4/20895836/ai-climate-change-economist-essay-contest-gpt2|title=The Economist\u2019s essay contest featured an AI submission. Here\u2019s what the judges thought.|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2019-10-04|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Data journalism ==\n[[File:A_graphic_detail_of_The_Economist.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:A_graphic_detail_of_The_Economist.jpg|thumb|The paper launched a large [[data journalism]] platform in 2015, tasked with creating and developing [[Graphical model|graphical models]] for ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] coverage.]]\nThe presence of [[data journalism]] in ''The Economist'' can be traced to its founding year in 1843. Initially, the weekly published basic [[international trade]] figures and tables.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/data-journalism-at-the-economist-gets-a-home-of-its-own-in-print-92e194c7f67e|title=Data journalism at The Economist gets a home of its own in print|last=Selby-Boothroyd|first=Alex|date=2018-10-18|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/read/newsletters/ama-with-the-economists-data-team|title=AMA with The Economist's data team - Newsletter|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The paper first included a graphical model in 1847, with a [[bubble chart]] detailing [[Precious metal|precious metals]], and its first [[Epistolary novel|non-epistolary chart]] was included in its 1854 issue, charting the [[Cholera|spread of cholera]].<ref name=\":02\" /> This early adoption of data-based articles was estimated to be \"a 100 years before [[Dot-com bubble|the field\u2019s modern emergence]]\" by ''Data Journalism.com.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/read/newsletters/ama-with-the-economists-data-team|title=AMA with The Economist's data team - Newsletter|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Its transition from [[broadsheet]] to [[magazine]]-style formatting led to the adoption of colored graphs, first in [[Fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] during the 1980s and then to a thematic blue in 2001.<ref name=\":02\" /> The ''Economist'' told their readers throughout the 2000s that the paper's editors had \"developed a taste for data-driven stories.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Starting in the late-2000s, they began to publish more and more articles that centered solely on charts, some of which began to be published daily.<ref name=\":02\" /> The daily charts are typically followed by a short, 300-word explanation. In September 2009, ''The Economist'' launched a [[Twitter]] account for their Data Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ECONdailycharts|title=The Economist Data Team (@ECONdailycharts) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the weekly formed a dedicated team of 12 [[Data analysis|data analysts]], designers, and journalists to head up their firm-wide data journalism efforts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/economist-using-12-person-data-journalism-team-drive-subscriptions/|title=How The Economist uses its 12-person data journalism team to drive subscriptions|date=2018-05-04|website=Digiday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> In order to ensure transparency in their data collection ''The Economist'' maintains a corporate [[GitHub]] account to publicly disclosure all of their models and software.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/turning-a-page-the-economists-data-journalism-gets-its-own-place-in-print-664c2e5bdfe9|title=Turning a page: The Economist\u2019s data journalism gets its own place in print|last=Economist|first=The|date=2018-10-22|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> In October 2018, they introduced their \"Graphic Detail\" feature in both their print and digital editions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Graphic Detail feature would go on to include mainly graphs, maps, and [[Infographic|infographics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journalism.co.uk/news/the-economist-s-print-edition-launches-a-dedicated-data-journalism-page-for-better-visual-storytelling/s2/a729384/|title=The Economist's print edition launches a dedicated data journalism page for better visual storytelling {{!}} Media news|date=2018-10-23|website=www.journalism.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s Data Team won the 2020 Sigma Data Journalism Award for Best Young Journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/awards|title=Sigma Data Journalism Awards|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020|quote=G. Elliott Morris, Organisation: The Economist (United States)}}</ref> In 2015, they placed third for an infographic describing [[Politics of Israel|Israel's coalition networks]] in the year's Data Journalism Awards by the [[Global Editors Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaleditorsnetwork.org/programmes/data-journalism-awards/dja-newsletter/|title=DJA Newsletter|last=|first=|date=|website=GEN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020|quote=To explain something complex doesn\u2019t always require an interactive graphic. This look by The Economist\u2019s  team illustrates the complexities of Israeli politics in one long chart where it pays to scroll \u2014 and which would work equally well in print as online.}}</ref>\n\n=== Indexes ===\nHistorically, the publication has also maintained a section of [[economic statistics]], such as employment figures, economic growth, and interest rates. These statistical publications have been found to be seen as authoritative and decisive in British society.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3WVLKKSOcGYC&pg=PA88|title=Great expectations\u2014the social sciences in Great Britain|publisher=Commission on the Social Sciences|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7658-0849-3|page=88}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also publishes a variety of rankings seeking to position [[Business school|business schools]] and and [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate universities]] among each other, respectively. In 2015, they publish their first ranking of U.S. universities, focusing on comparable economical advantages. Their data for the rankings is sourced from the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] and is calculated as a function of median earnings through [[regression analysis]].<ref>{{cite journal|date=29 October 2015|title=The Economist \"The value of university: Our first-ever college rankings\"|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2015/10/value-university|journal=The Economist|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> Among others, the most well-known [[Index (economics)|data indexes]] the weekly publishes are:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* The [[Big Mac Index]]: a measure of the [[Purchasing power parity|purchasing power]] of currencies, first published in 1986, using the price of the hamburger in different countries.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Paul R. Krugman, Maurice Obstfeld|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NZnk5C2r8qEC&pg=PA396|title=International Economics|publisher=Pearson Education|year=2009|isbn=978-0-321-55398-0|page=396}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=6\u201312 September 1986|title=On the Hamburger Standard|journal=The Economist}}</ref> This is published twice a year, annually.\n* The Glass Ceiling Index: a measure of [[Occupational sexism|female equality in the workplace]].\n* The Most Dangerous Cities Index: a measure of major cities [[List of countries by intentional homicide rate|by rates of homicide]].\n\n==Opinions==\n{{Main|The Economist editorial stance}}\n\nThe editorial stance of ''The Economist'' primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]] and [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring polices and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper favors [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/17732859|title=Globalisation: The redistribution of hope|date=16 December 2010|work=The Economist|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref> When the newspaper was founded, the term \"[[economism]]\" denoted what would today be termed \"[[economic liberalism]]\". The activist and journalist [[George Monbiot]] has described it as [[neoliberalism|neo-liberal]] while occasionally accepting the propositions of [[Keynesian economics]] where deemed more \"reasonable\".<ref name=\"Grauniad\">{{cite news|author=George Monbiot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/jan/11/economy.g8|title=George Monbiot, Punitive \u2013 and it works|date=11 January 2005|work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 May 2012|location=London}}</ref> The weekly favours a [[carbon tax]] to fight [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite journal|date=14 June 2008|title=Buttonwood: Let them heat coke|url=https://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11543656|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> According to one former editor, Bill Emmott, \"the ''Economist''{{'}}s philosophy has always been liberal, not conservative\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Emmot|first=Bill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/monarchy/story/0,2763,408484,00.html|title=Time for a referendum on the monarchy|date=8 December 2000|work=Comment|accessdate=27 December 2006|location=London}}</ref> [[File:David Hume and Adam Smith statues.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[Adam Smith]] (''right'') and philosopher [[David Hume]] (''left'') represent the newspaper's foundational beliefs of ''[[laissez-faire]]'' [[Economic policy|policies]], [[self-sufficiency]], [[Protectionism|anti-protectionism]] and [[free trade]].|alt=]]Individual contributors take diverse views. ''The Economist'' favours the support, through [[central bank]]s, of banks and other important corporations. This principle can, in a much more limited form, be traced back to [[Walter Bagehot]], the third editor of ''The Economist'', who argued that the Bank of England should support major banks that got into difficulties. [[Karl Marx]] deemed ''The Economist'' the \"European organ\" of \"the aristocracy of finance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Marx|first=Karl|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1852/18th-brumaire/ch06.htm|title=The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte|year=1852}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper has also supported liberal causes on social issues such as recognition of gay marriages,<ref>[https://www.economist.com/PrinterFriendly.cfm?story_id=2515389 Let them wed], cover article on 4 January 1996</ref> legalisation of drugs,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100602002643/http://www.drogasedemocracia.org/Arquivos/the-economist.pdf How to stop the drug wars], cover article on 7 March 2009.  The publication calls legalisation \"the least bad solution\".</ref> criticises the [[Taxation in the United States|US tax model]],<ref>{{cite journal|date=4 February 2012|title=Tax reform in America: A simple bare necessity|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21545981|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> and seems to support some government regulation on health issues, such as smoking in public,<ref>{{cite journal|date=10 June 2010|title=Smoking and public health: Breathe easy|url=https://www.economist.com/node/16333351|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> as well as bans on spanking children.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11455006 \"Spare The Rod, Say Some\"], ''The Economist'', 31 May 2008.</ref> ''The Economist'' consistently favours guest worker programmes, parental choice of school, and amnesties<ref>[https://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=6744217 Sense, not Sensenbrenner], The Economist, 30 March 2006</ref> and once published an \"obituary\" of God.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/obituary/1999/12/23/god|title=Obituary: God|date=23 December 1999|work=The Economist|access-date=}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also has a long record of supporting gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/13447986|title=Lexington: Reflections on Virginia Tech|date=8 April 2009|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' has endorsed the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (in 2005), the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] (in 2010 and 2015),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/29/the-economist-backs-conservatives \"The Economist backs the Conservatives\"], ''The Guardian'' (PA report), 29 April 2010.</ref><ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite journal|date=2 May 2015|title=Who should govern Britain?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21650113-despite-risk-europe-coalition-led-david-cameron-should-have-second-term-who|journal=The Economist|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref> and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (in 2017 and 2019) at general election time in Britain, and both [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidates in the United States. ''Economist.com'' puts its stance this way:\n\n{{quotation|What, besides free trade and free markets, does ''The Economist'' believe in? \"It is to the Radicals that ''The Economist'' still likes to think of itself as belonging. The extreme centre is the paper's historical position\". That is as true today as when Crowther [Geoffrey, ''Economist'' editor 1938\u20131956] said it in 1955. ''The Economist'' considers itself the enemy of privilege, pomposity and predictability. It has backed conservatives such as [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]]. It has supported the Americans in [[Vietnam]]. But it has also endorsed [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Bill Clinton]], and espoused a variety of liberal causes: opposing capital punishment from its earliest days, while favouring penal reform and decolonisation, as well as\u2014more recently\u2014gun control and gay marriage.<ref name=\"About us\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/help/about-us#About_The_Economist|title=About us|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>}}\n''The Economist'' frequently accuses figures and countries of corruption or dishonesty. In recent years, for example, it criticised [[Paul Wolfowitz]], [[World Bank]] president; [[Silvio Berlusconi]], Italy's Prime Minister (who dubbed it ''The Ecommunist'');<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2005/09/324682.html|title=Report of Rome anti-war demo on Saturday 24th with photos|work=[[Independent Media Center]]|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]], the late president of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]; [[Robert Mugabe]], the former head of government in [[Zimbabwe]]; and, recently, [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]], the president of Argentina.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/la/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11293743|title=Cristina in the land of make believe|date=1 May 2008|work=The Economist}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also called for [[impeachment of Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton's impeachment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/1998/09/17/just-go|title=Just go|date=1998-09-17|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> and, after the emergence of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=2647493|title=Resign Rumsfeld|date=6 May 2004|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> for [[Donald Rumsfeld]]'s resignation. Though ''The Economist'' initially gave vigorous support for the [[Iraq War|US-led invasion of Iraq]], it later called the operation \"bungled from the start\" and criticised the \"almost criminal negligence\" of the Bush Administration's handling of the war, while maintaining, in 2007, that pulling out in the short term would be irresponsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RRRTGGP|title=Mugged by reality|date=22 March 2007|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 April 2007}}</ref> In the 2004 US election, the editors \"reluctantly\" backed John Kerry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_QTVPPQ|title=Crunch time in America|date=2 November 2000|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=3329802|title=The incompetent or the incoherent?|date=28 October 2004|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> In the 2008 US election ''The Economist'' endorsed [[Barack Obama]], while using the front cover of the issue published on the eve of the election to promote his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?source=most_commented&story_id=12511171|title=It's time|date=30 October 2008|work=The Economist}}</ref> In the 2012 US election, Barack Obama was again endorsed: the editorial said that they preferred Obama on the economy, foreign policy and health care, but criticised him for running a negative campaign against Romney and for a \"...poor appreciation of commerce.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21565623-america-could-do-better-barack-obama-sadly-mitt-romney-does-not-fit-bill-which-one?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709|title=Our American Endorsement. Which one?|date=3 November 2012|newspaper=The Economist|accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the Economist endorse [[Hillary Clinton]], and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] due \"[p]artly because she is not Mr Trump, but also in the hope she can show that ordinary politics works for ordinary people\u2014the sort of renewal that American democracy requires.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2016/11/05/americas-best-hope|title=America's best hope|date=2016-11-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nIn an editorial marking its 175th anniversary, ''The Economist'' criticised adherents to liberalism for becoming too inclined to protect the political status quo rather than pursue reform.<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/essay/2018/09/13/the-economist-at-175|title=The Economist at 175|date=13 September 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>{{Non-primary source needed|date=May 2019}} The paper called on liberals to return to advocating for bold political, economic and social reforms: protecting [[free market]]s, land and tax reform in the tradition of [[Georgism]], [[open immigration]], a rethink of the [[social contract]] with more emphasis on education, and a revival of [[liberal internationalism]].<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\" />\n\n==Circulation==\n[[File:The Economist Display.jpg|thumb|A display of newspapers in [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]] supermarket, depicting the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\nEach of ''The Economist'' issue's official date range is from Saturday to the following Friday. ''The Economist'' posts each week's new content online at approximately 2100 Thursday evening UK time, ahead of the official publication date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/08/service-announcement|title=The Economist launches on Android|date=2 August 2011|work=The Economist|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> From July to December 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million.<ref name=\"pgazette\" /> However, on a weekly average basis, the paper can reach up to 5.1 million readers, across their print and digital runs.<ref name=\"pgazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/economist-boasts-15m-magazine-circulation-and-36m-social-media-followers/|title=The Economist boasts 1.5m magazine circulation and 36m social media followers|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date=March 8, 2016|website=Press Gazette|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1877, the publication's circulation was 3,700, and in 1920 it had risen to 6,000. Circulation increased rapidly after 1945, reaching 100,000 by 1970.<ref name=\"About us\" /> Circulation is audited by the [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]] (ABC). From around 30,000 in 1960 it has risen to near 1 million by 2000 and by 2016 to about 1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Lucinda Southern|date=17 February 2016|title=The Economist Plans to Double Circulation Profits in 5 Years|url=http://digiday.com/publishers/economist-aims-double-circulation-profits-5-years/|magazine=[[Digiday]]|access-date=7 July 2016}}</ref> Sales inside North America were in 2007 around 54 per cent of the total, with sales in the UK making up 14 per cent of the total and continental Europe 19 per cent. ''The Economist'' claims sales, both by subscription and at newsagents, in over 200 countries. Of its American readers, two out of three earn more than $100,000 a year.<ref name=\"gainsreaders\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5250996|title='Economist' Magazine Wins American Readers|date=8 March 2006|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]]|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' once boasted about its limited circulation. In the early 1990s it used the slogan \"''The Economist'' \u2013 not read by millions of people\". \"Never in the history of journalism has so much been read for so long by so few,\" wrote [[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]], a former editor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moseley|first=Ray|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D3B56996BE43&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=\"Economist\" aspires to influence, and many say it does.|work=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=14 May 2008|format=pay archive}}</ref>\n\nThe Economist Newspaper Limited is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[The Economist Group]]. The publications of the group include the ''CFO'' brand family as well as the annual ''The World in...'', and the bimonthly [[lifestyle magazine]], ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]].'' Sir [[Evelyn Robert de Rothschild]] was Chairman of the company from 1972 to 1989.\n\n==Censorship==\n[[File:A page ripped out from The Economist by China's censorship department (cropped).jpg|thumb|232x232px|A page ripped out from ''The Economist'' by China's censorship department in [[Liaoning Provincial Museum|Liaoning Provincial Library]]. ]]\nSections of ''The Economist'' criticising authoritarian regimes are frequently removed from the paper by the authorities in those countries. ''The Economist'' regularly has difficulties with the ruling party of Singapore, the [[People's Action Party]], which had successfully sued it, in a Singaporean court, for [[Defamation|libel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/HL01Ae01.html|title=Inconvenient truths in Singapore|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[Asia Times]] }}</ref>\n\nLike many other publications, ''The Economist'' is subjected to censorship in [[India]] whenever it depicts a map of [[Kashmir]]. The maps are stamped by Indian Customs officials as being \"neither correct, nor authentic\". Issues are sometimes delayed, but not stopped or seized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/12/censorship_india|title=Censorship in India|work=The Economist | date=7 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, [[Iran]] banned the sale of ''The Economist'' when it published a map labelling the [[Persian Gulf]] simply as Gulf\u2014a choice that derives its political significance from the [[Persian Gulf naming dispute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1150191582529&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Iran bans ''The Economist'' over map|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, the government of [[Zimbabwe]] went further and imprisoned ''The Economist''{{'}}s correspondent there, [[Andrew Meldrum]]. The government charged him with violating a statute on \"publishing untruth\" for writing that a woman was decapitated by supporters of the ruling [[Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] party. The [[decapitation]] claim was retracted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |title=Guardian and RFI correspondent risks two years in jail |accessdate=2 April 2014 |work=[[Reporters Without Borders]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404211952/http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |archivedate=4 April 2009 }}</ref> and allegedly fabricated by the woman's husband. The correspondent was later acquitted, only to receive a [[deportation]] order.\n\nOn 19 August 2013, ''The Economist'' disclosed that the Missouri Department of Corrections had censored its issue of 29 June 2013. According to the letter sent by the department, prisoners were not allowed to receive the issue because \"1. it constitutes a threat to the security or discipline of the institution; 2. may facilitate or encourage criminal activity; or 3. may interfere with the rehabilitation of an offender\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist in prison: About that missing issue|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2013/08/economist-prison|work=The Economist|accessdate=2 April 2014|date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of business newspapers]]\n* [[List of newspapers in the United Kingdom]]\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Media|Business|News|United Kingdom|Europe}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Arrese, Angel (1995), ''La identidad de The Economist,'' Pamplona: Eunsa. {{ISBN|9788431313739}}. ([https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326415042_La_identidad_de_The_Economist preview])\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thebalancesmb.com/best-business-magazines-4176680|title=The 8 Best Business Magazines of 2020|last=Delbridge|first=Emily|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Balance Small Business|publisher=Dotdash|location=New York City|page=|pages=|at=Best Economics Reporting: The Economist|doi=|pmid=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 Feb 2020|magazine=}}\n* Edwards, Ruth Dudley (1993), ''The Pursuit of Reason: The Economist 1843\u20131993'', London: Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-12939-7}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Media Monoliths|author=Tungate|first=Mark|location=|pages=194\u2013206|chapter=''The Economist''|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7494-4108-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|The_Economist.ogg|12 July 2006}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.economist.com/}}\n* {{HathiTrust Catalog}}\n\n{{Rothschilds}}\n{{The Economist Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economist, The}}\n\n<!--Do not add any categories about newsmagazine or magazines, The Economist is a newspaper, printed in magazine-format.-->\n[[Category:The Economist]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International newspapers]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Websites utilizing paywalls]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the profession|Economist|6=other uses|7=The Economist (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|English weekly news and international affairs publication}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Economist\n| logo = The Economist Logo.svg\n| image = 'The Economist' cover (September 8, 2001).png\n| caption = Cover of the 8 September 2001 issue{{#tag:ref|The title and its design are references to the book ''[[No Logo]]'' (1999).|group=\"nb\"}}\n| type = [[Weekly newspaper]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n| format = <!--The Economist is a newspaper printed in magazine format. Leave as \"magazine\" for format, with no hyperlink.-->Magazine\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1843|09}}\n| founder = [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]\n| owners = [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]]\n| ISSN = 0013-0613\n| political = <!--This is not an indiscriminate list, only the big, umbrella political camps The Economist belongs to.-->\n[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eb87e2f4-ffc9-11e9-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Liberalism at Large \u2014 how The Economist gets it right and spectacularly wrong|last=Zevin|first=Alexander|date=December 20, 2019|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Social liberalism]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/11/liberalism-according-to-the-economist|title=Liberalism According to The Economist|last=Mishra|first=Pankaj|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>[[Radical centrism]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-0|work=The Economist|title=Is The Economist left- or right-wing?|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21564556|work=The Economist|title=True Progressivism|date=13 October 2012|accessdate=16 October 2016}}</ref>\n| headquarters = [[Adelphi, London|1-11 John Adam Street]]<br>[[City of Westminster|Westminster]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| editor = [[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]\n| website = {{url|economist.com}}\n| circulation = 909,476 (print)<br>748,459 (digital)<br>1.6 million (combined)\n| circulation_date = July-December 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=The Economist - Data - ABC {{!}} Audit Bureau of Circulations |url=https://www.abc.org.uk/product/432 |website=www.abc.org.uk}}</ref>\n| logo_size = 135px\n| depeditor = [[Tom Standage]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Economist''''' is an international [[weekly newspaper]] <!--It is a newspaper NOT a magazine. Please see discussion at Talk:The Economist/Archive 2. The latter is \"printing format\" NOT a publication. Do not change wording without another editorial consensus on the talk as per WP:TITLE it is still a newspaper no matter how it is printed.-->printed in [[Magazine|magazine-format]] that focuses on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]], [[world news]], international business, and politics. Based in [[London|London, England]], the newspaper is owned by [[Economist Group|The Economist Group]], with core  editorial offices in major cities in North America, Europe, Asia, and the [[Middle East]]. In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million). In 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million. Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016. The newspaper has a prominent focus on [[data journalism]] and analysis over [[News media|original reporting]], to both criticism and acclaim.<!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Article uses British English, e.g. \"-ise\" over \"-ize\". See: WP:ISE.--><!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->\n\nFounded in 1843, ''The Economist'' was first circulated by Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] to muster support for abolishing the British [[Corn Laws]] (1815\u201346), a system of [[Tariff|import tariffs]]. Over time, the newspaper's coverage expanded further into [[political economy]] and eventually began running articles on current events, finance, commerce, and British politics. Throughout the mid- to late- 20th century, it greatly expanded its layout and format, adding [[Op-ed|opinion columns]], special reports, [[Political cartoon|political cartoons]], [[Letter to the editor|reader letters]], cover stories, art critique, book reviews, and technology features. The paper is often recognizable by its [[fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] nameplate and illustrated, topical covers. Individual articles are written anonymously, with [[Byline|no byline]], in order for the paper to speak as one collective voice. The paper is supplemented by its sister lifestyle magazine, ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]]'', and a variety of podcasts, films, and books.\n\nThe [[The Economist editorial stance|editorial stance of ''The Economist'']] primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]], [[Social liberalism|social]], and most notably, [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring policies and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper advocates for [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]]. Despite a pronounced editorial stance, it is seen as having little [[reporting bias]], rigorous [[Fact-checking|fact checking]] and strict [[copy editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/when-will-magazines-stop-trying-to-copy-the-economist|title=Why Time and Newsweek Will Never Be The Economist|last=Pressman|first=Matt|date=April 20, 2009|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2017/02/01/10-journalism-brands-where-you-will-find-real-facts-rather-than-alternative-facts/|title=10 Journalism Brands Where You Find Real Facts Rather Than Alternative Facts|last=Leadership|first=The Berlin School Of Creative|date=February 1, 2017|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Its extensive use of [[Word play|word play]], [[Subscription (finance)|subscription]] prices, and typical depth of coverage has linked the paper with a high-income and educated readership, drawing both positive and negative connotations in the [[Western world|Western World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/01/31/why-the-economist-swapped-its-famous-elitist-marketing-emotional-messaging|title=Why The Economist swapped its famous elitist marketing for emotional messaging|last=Burnell|first=Ian|date=31 January 2019|website=The Drum|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/09/business/media/09economist.html|title=The Economist Tends Its Sophisticate Garden|date=2010-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In line with this, it claims to have influential readership of prominent business leaders and [[Policy|policy-makers]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:James Wilson by Sir John Watson-Gordon.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] founded the newspaper to \"take part in a severe [[Debate|contest between intelligence]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reed.edu/reed-magazine/articles/2017/contest-letter-editor.html|title=The Contest|last=Lydgate|first=Chris|date=March 1, 2017|website=Reed Magazine|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2017}}</ref>|208x208px]]\n''The Economist'' was founded by the British businessman and banker [[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]] in 1843, to advance the repeal of the [[Corn Laws]], a system of import tariffs.<ref>[http://mitpress.typepad.com/mitpresslog/2007/01/from_corn_laws_.html From the Corn Laws to Your Mailbox], The MIT Press Log, 30 January 2007. Retrieved 11 June 2010.</ref> A [[prospectus (finance)|prospectus]] for the \"newspaper\" from 5 August 1843 enumerated thirteen areas of coverage that its editors wanted the publication to focus on:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=1873493|title=Prospectus|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist|date=5 August 1843}}</ref>\n# Original [[editorial|leading articles]], in which free-trade principles will be most rigidly applied to all the important questions of the day.\n# Articles relating to some practical, commercial, agricultural, or foreign topic of passing interest, such as foreign treaties.\n# An article on the elementary principles of [[political economy]], applied to practical experience, covering the laws related to prices, wages, rent, exchange, revenue and taxes.\n# [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliamentary]] reports, with particular focus on commerce, agriculture and free trade.\n# Reports and accounts of popular movements advocating free trade.\n# General news from the [[Court of St. James's]], the [[Greater London|Metropolis]], the [[Historic counties of England|Provinces]], Scotland, and Ireland.\n# Commercial topics such as changes in fiscal regulations, the state and prospects of the markets, imports and exports, foreign news, the state of the manufacturing districts, notices of important new mechanical improvements, shipping news, the money market, and the progress of railways and public companies.\n# Agricultural topics, including the application of geology and [[chemistry]]; notices of new and improved [[List of agricultural machinery|implements]], state of crops, markets, prices, foreign markets and prices converted into English money; from time to time, in some detail, the plans pursued in Belgium, Switzerland, and other well-cultivated countries.\n# [[British overseas territories|Colonial]] and foreign topics, including trade, produce, political and fiscal changes, and other matters, including [[Investigative journalism|expos\u00e9s]] on the evils of restriction and protection, and the advantages of free intercourse and trade.\n# Law reports, confined chiefly to areas important to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture.\n# Books, confined chiefly, but not so exclusively, to commerce, manufacturing, and agriculture, and including all treatises on political economy, finance, or taxation.\n# A commercial [[gazette]], with prices and statistics of the week.\n# [[Letter to the editor|Correspondence and inquiries]] from the newspaper's readers.\n\nWilson described it as taking part in \"a severe contest between intelligence, which presses forward, and an unworthy, timid ignorance obstructing our progress\", a phrase which still appears on its masthead as the publication's mission.<ref name=\"opinion\">{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/ |title=Opinion: leaders and letters to the Editor |work=The Economist |accessdate=1 May 2011}}</ref> It has long been respected as \"one of the most competent and subtle Western periodicals on public affairs\".<ref name=\"Leites\">{{cite journal|title=The Politburo Through Western Eyes|pages=159\u2013185|author=Nathan Leites|journal=[[World Politics]]|year=1952|volume=4|issue=2|jstor=2009044|doi=10.2307/2009044}}{{subscription required}}</ref> It was cited by [[Karl Marx]] in his formulation of socialist theory, because Marx felt the publication epitomised the interests of the bourgeoisie <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YauuCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA242&dq=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&pg=PA242#v=onepage&q=%22the%20london%20economist%22%20read%20by%20marx&f=false|title=Karl Marx: His Life and Thought|last=McLellan|first=David|date=1 December 1973|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781349155149|language=en}}</ref> He wrote: \"the London ''Economist'', the European organ of the aristocracy of finance, described most strikingly the attitude of this class.\"<ref>Karl Marx, ''The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte'', VI (1852)</ref> In 1915, revolutionary [[Vladimir Lenin]] referred to ''The Economist'' as a \"journal that speaks for British millionaires\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theeconomist/status/955168910852153344?lang=en|author=The Economist|website=twitter.com}}</ref> Additionally Lenin claimed that ''The Economist'' held a \"bourgeois-pacifist\" position and supported peace out of fear of [[revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1915/may/01c.htm|title=Bourgeois Philanthropists and Revolutionary Social-Democracy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:The Economist 2019 1 o.jpg|left|thumb|A panel of journalists and public policy leaders at ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s 2019 India Summit.<nowiki/>]]In 1920, the paper's circulation rose to 6,170.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} In 1934, it underwent its first major redesign. The current [[fire engine red]] nameplate was created by [[Reynolds Stone]] in 1959.<ref name=\"About us\" /> In January 2012, ''The Economist'' launched a new weekly section devoted exclusively to China, the first new country section since the introduction of one on the United States in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economist Launches New China Section|url=http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|work=Asian Media Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201210032/http://www.asiamediajournal.com/pressrelease.php?id=3277|archivedate=1 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 1991, [[James Fallows]] argued in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that ''The Economist'' used editorial lines that contradicted the news stories they purported to highlight.<ref name=\"fallows\" /> In 1999, [[Andrew Sullivan]] complained in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that it uses \"marketing genius\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/london-fog|title=London Fog|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> to make up for deficiencies in original reporting, resulting in \"a kind of ''[[Reader's Digest]]''\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3874750,00.html|title=Not so groovy.|date=14 June 1999|work=The New Republic|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref> for America's corporate elite.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Finkel|first=Rebecca|date=July 1999|title=Nasty barbs fly between New Republic and Economist|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/news1999/july99/news4707.html|magazine=Media Life|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107024913/http://www.medialifemagazine.com:8080/news1999/july99/news4707.html|archivedate=7 November 2015|accessdate=27 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"its writers rarely see a political or economic problem that cannot be solved by the trusted three-card trick of privatisation, deregulation and liberalisation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Stern|first=Stefan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/aug/21/pressandpublishing.business1|title=Economist thrives on female intuition|date=21 August 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 January 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' named it the best English-language paper noting its strength in international reporting where it does not feel moved to cover a faraway land only at a time of unmitigated disaster\" and that it kept a wall between its reporting and its more conservative editorial policies.<ref>Entertainment: 50 Best Magazines, Chicago Tribune, 15 June 2006.</ref> In 2008, [[Jon Meacham]], former editor of ''Newsweek'' and a self-described \"fan\", criticised ''The Economist''{{'s}} focus on analysis over original reporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/node/39374|title=Jon Meacham Wants Newsweek to Be More Like Hayes' Esquire|work=The New York Observer|accessdate=27 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522125448/http://www.observer.com/node/39374|archive-date=22 May 2008}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Economist'' was [[2012 ICT Skype controversy|accused]] of hacking into the computer of Justice [[Mohammed Nizamul Huq]] of the [[Bangladesh]] Supreme Court, leading to his resignation as the chairman of the [[International Crimes Tribunal (Bangladesh)|International Crimes Tribunal]].<ref name=\"ICTleaks\">{{cite magazine|date=8 December 2012|title=Discrepancy in Dhaka|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/12/bangladesh|magazine=The Economist}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/bangladesh-crimes-tribunal-accuses-the-economist-magazine-of-hacking-judges-computer/2012/12/09/8f248da2-421e-11e2-8c8f-fbebf7ccab4e_story.html|title=Economist accused of hacking ICT judge's computer|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks2\">{{cite news|last=Hossain|first=Farid|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20121209/as-bangladesh-war-crimes|title=Economist magazine faces contempt in Bangladesh|date=9 December 2012|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=\"ICTleaks3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/bangladeshi-war-crimes-tribunal-issues-notice-to-the-economist/1041394|title=Bangladeshi war crimes tribunal issues notice to The Economist|date=6 December 2012|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> In August 2015, [[Pearson plc|Pearson]] sold its 50% stake in the newspaper to the Italian [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company, [[Exor (company)|Exor]], for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]469 million ([[United States dollar|US$]]531 million) and the paper re-acquired the remaining shares for \u00a3182 million ($206 million).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-economist-pearson_55cb31f0e4b0923c12beac28?ir=Business&section=business&kvcommref=mostpopular|title=Pearson Unloads $731 Million Stake in the Economist|date=12 August 2015|work=HuffPost|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Shareholders ===\n[[File:Economist building London1.jpg|thumb|The Economist Building, until 2017, in [[London]], England on [[St James's Street]].|alt=]][[Pearson plc]] held a 50% shareholding via [[Financial Times|The Financial Times Limited]] until August 2015. At that time, Pearson sold their share in the Economist. The [[Agnelli family]]'s [[Exor (company)|Exor]] paid \u00a3287m to raise their stake from 4.7% to 43.4% while the Economist paid \u00a3182m for the balance of 5.04m shares which will be distributed to current shareholders.<ref name=\"West\">{{cite news|last=West|first=Karl|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/aug/15/economist-becomes-a-family-affair-agnellis|title=The Economist becomes a family affair|date=15 August 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=15 August 2015|location=London|quote=Pearson, the education and publishing giant that has held a non-controlling 50% stake since 1928, is selling the holding for \u00a3469m. The deal will make Italy's Agnelli family, founders of the Fiat car empire, the largest shareholder}}</ref> Aside from the Agnelli family, smaller shareholders in the company include [[Cadbury family|Cadbury]], [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]] (21%), [[Schroders|Schroder]], [[Baron Layton|Layton]] and other family interests as well as a number of staff and former staff shareholders.<ref name=\"West\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/agnellis-rothschilds-close-in-on-economist-magazine-sale-pearson/|title=Agnellis, Rothschilds close in on Economist|date=11 August 2015|work=POLITICO|access-date=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Trustee|board of trustees]] formally appoints the editor, who cannot be removed without its permission. Although ''The Economist'' has a global emphasis and scope, about two-thirds of the 75 staff journalists are based in the London borough of [[City of Westminster|Westminster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/so-whats-the-secret-of-the-economist-347699.html|title=So what's the secret of 'The Economist'?|date=26 February 2006|work=The Independent|accessdate=27 April 2008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Editor ===\n[[File:Zanny Minton Beddoes World Economic Forum 2013 cropped.jpg|thumb|254x254px|[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]] was appointed editor in 2015, first joining as an [[emerging markets]] correspondent in 1994.]]\nThe [[editor-in-chief]], commonly known simply as \"the Editor\", of ''The Economist'' is charged with formulating the paper's editorial policies and overseeing corporate operations. Since its 1843 founding, the editors have been:\n\n*[[James Wilson (businessman)|James Wilson]]: 1843\u20131857\n*[[Richard Holt Hutton]]: 1857\u20131861<ref>The ''Concise Dictionary of National Biography'' makes him assistant editor 1858\u20131860</ref>\n*[[Walter Bagehot]]: 1861\u20131877<ref>He was Wilson's son-in-law</ref>\n*[[Daniel Conner Lathbury]]: 1877\u20131881<ref>[[s:The Times/1922/Obituary/Daniel Conner Lathbury|A journalist and biographer]]</ref> (''jointly'')\n*[[Robert Harry Inglis Palgrave]]: 1877\u20131883 (''jointly'')\n* Edward Johnstone: 1883\u20131907<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|title=economist150\u5468\u5e74\uff081993\uff09 \u2013 \u7ecf\u6d4e\u5b66\u4eba\u8d44\u6599\u5e93 \u2013 ECO\u4e2d\u6587\u7f51 \u2013 Powered by Discuz! Archiver|author=Discuz! Team and Comsenz UI Team|accessdate=29 June 2015|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922170122/http://www.ecocn.org/archiver/?tid-2398.html|archive-date=22 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Francis Wrigley Hirst]]: 1907\u20131916\n* Hartley Withers: 1916\u20131921\n*[[Walter Layton, 1st Baron Layton|Sir Walter Layton]]: 1922\u20131938\n*[[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]]: 1938\u20131956\n*[[Donald Tyerman]]: 1956\u20131965\n*[[Alastair Burnet|Sir Alastair Burnet]]: 1965\u20131974\n*[[Andrew Knight (journalist)|Andrew Knight]]: 1974\u20131986\n*[[Rupert Pennant-Rea]]: 1986\u20131993\n*[[Bill Emmott]]: 1993\u20132006\n*[[John Micklethwait]]: 2006\u20132014<ref>{{cite news|title=John Micklethwait leaving the Economist to join Bloomberg News|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/09/john-micklethwait-leaving-economist-joining-bloomberg|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 December 2014|last1=Sweney|first1=Mark}}</ref>\n*[[Zanny Minton Beddoes]]: 2015\u2013present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/zanny-minton-beddoes/|title=Zanny Minton Beddoes|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Tone and voice==\nThough it has many individual columns, by tradition and current practice the newspaper ensures a uniform voice\u2014aided by the anonymity of writers\u2014throughout its pages,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/styleguide/introduction|title=Style Guide | accessdate=8 February 2013|work=The Economist|date=27 September 2011}}</ref> as if most articles were written by a single author, which may be perceived to display dry, understated wit, and precise use of language.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/research/styleGuide/index.cfm?page=673927|title=The Economist \u2013 Tone|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |title=Johnson |accessdate=27 December 2006 |work=The Economist |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219221031/http://www.economist.com/research/johnson/ |archivedate=19 December 2006 }}</ref> <!--Article uses \"newspaper\", \"paper\", \"weekly\" to otherwise denote The Economist \u2013\u2013 not magazine or news magazine. See: Talk:The Economist/Archive 2.-->''The Economist'' has traditionally\u2014albeit not always consistently\u2014persisted in referring to itself as a \"[[newspaper]]\", rather than a \"[[news magazine]]\", due to [[Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|its legal classification as a newspaper]] in Britain, its transition from [[broadsheet]] to glossy colour format, and its general focus on [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] as opposed to specialist subjects.<ref name=\"pgazette\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/09/the-economist-is-a-newspaper-even-though-it-doesnt-look-like-one/|title=The Economist Is a Newspaper, Even Though It Doesn\u2019t Look Like One|date=2013-09-02|website=Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Iber|first=Patrick|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155962/liberalism-at-large-book-review-the-economist-magazine|title=The World The Economist Made|date=2019-12-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2020-04-08|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist''{{'}}s treatment of economics presumes a working familiarity with fundamental concepts of classical economics. For instance, it does not explain terms like [[invisible hand]], [[macroeconomics]], or [[demand curve]], and may take just six or seven words to explain the theory of [[comparative advantage]]. Articles involving economics do not presume any formal training on the part of the reader and aim to be accessible to the educated layman. It usually does not translate short French (and German) quotes or phrases. It does describe the business or nature of even well-known entities, writing, for example, \"[[Goldman Sachs]], an investment bank\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/britain/2008/02/21/a-bank-by-any-other-name|title=A bank by any other name|date=2008-02-21|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' is known for its extensive use of [[word play]], including puns, allusions, and metaphors, as well as alliteration and assonance, especially in its headlines and captions. This can make it difficult to understand for those who are not native English speakers.<ref>Richard J. Alexander, \"Article Headlines in ''The Economist'': An Analysis of Puns, Allusions and Metaphors\", ''Arbeiten aus Anglistik und Amerikanistik '''11''':2:159-177 (1986) {{jstor|43023400}}''</ref>\n\n===Editorial anonymity===\n[[File:The Economist Article.jpg|thumb|''Economist'' articles typically do not carry [[Byline|bylines]], anonymously publishing their work. |211x211px]]\nArticles often take a definite editorial stance and almost never carry a [[byline]]. Not even the name of the editor is printed in the issue. It is a long-standing tradition that an editor's only signed article during their tenure is written on the occasion of their departure from the position. The author of a piece is named in certain circumstances: when notable persons are invited to contribute opinion pieces; when journalists of ''The Economist'' compile special reports (previously known as surveys); for the Year in Review special edition; and to highlight a potential [[conflict of interest]] over a book review. The names of ''The Economist'' editors and correspondents can be located on the media directory pages of the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory|title=Media directory|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Online blog pieces are signed with the initials of the writer and authors of print stories are allowed to note their authorship from their personal web sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://andreaskluth.org/2008/11/20/why-the-economist-has-no-bylines/|title=Why The Economist has no bylines |work=Andreaskluth.org|accessdate=25 May 2012|date=20 November 2008 }}</ref> \"This approach is not without its faults (we have four staff members with the initials \"J.P.\", for example) but is the best compromise between total anonymity and full bylines, in our view\", wrote one anonymous writer of The Economist.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2013/09/economist-explains-itself-1/|title=Why are The Economist's writers anonymous? |journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 September 2016|date=4 September 2013 }}</ref> There are three editorial and business areas in which the anonymous ethos of the weekly has contributed to strengthening its unique identity: collective and consistent voice, talent and newsroom management, and brand strength and clarity. <ref>{{cite journal |last=Arrese |first=\u00c1ngel |title=\"\u201cIt\u2019s Anonymous. It\u2019s The Economist\u201d. The Journalistic and Business Value of Anonymity\" |journal=Journalism Practice |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2020.1735489}}</ref>\n\nThe editors say this is necessary because \"collective voice and personality matter more than the identities of individual journalists\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/help/about-us|title=The Economist \u2013 About us|accessdate=11 June 2012|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> and reflects \"a collaborative effort\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|title=Economist Editor Micklethwait brings his global perspective to the Twin Cities|accessdate=16 September 2008|date=29 April 2008|publisher=MinnPost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705161308/http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/04/29/1659/economist_editor_micklethwait_brings_his_global_perspective_to_the_twin_cities|archive-date=5 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> In most articles, authors refer to themselves as \"your correspondent\" or \"this reviewer\". The writers of the titled opinion columns tend to refer to themselves by the title (hence, a sentence in the \"Lexington\" column might read \"Lexington was informed...\").\n\nAmerican author and long-time reader [[Michael Lewis (author)|Michael Lewis]] criticised the paper's editorial anonymity in 1991, labelling it a means to hide the youth and inexperience of those writing articles.<ref name=\"fallows\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/1991/10/-quot-the-economics-of-the-colonial-cringe-quot-about-the-economist-magazine-washington-post-1991/7415/|title=The Economics of the Colonial Cringe: Pseudonomics and the Sneer on the Face of The Economist.|accessdate=27 April 2008|work=The Washington Post|date=16 October 1991}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2019/07/01/bestselling-author-michael-lewis-has-it-all-figured-out/|title=Bestselling Author Michael Lewis Has It All Figured Out|last=High|first=Peter|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Although individual articles are written anonymously, there is no secrecy over who the writers are as they are listed on ''The Economist''{{'s}} website, which also provides summaries of their careers and academic qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media directory|url=http://mediadirectory.economist.com/|work=The Economist|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Later, in 2009, Lewis included multiple ''Economist'' articles in his [[anthology]] about the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], ''[[Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lewis|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Panic.html?id=ZXUOASHVf_YC|title=Panic: The Story of Modern Financial Insanity|date=2009|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-06514-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[John Ralston Saul]] describes ''The Economist'' as a \"...[newspaper] which hides the names of the journalists who write its articles in order to create the illusion that they dispense disinterested truth rather than opinion. This sales technique, reminiscent of pre-Reformation Catholicism, is not surprising in a publication named after the social science most given to wild guesses and imaginary facts presented in the guise of inevitability and exactitude. That it is the Bible of the corporate executive indicates to what extent received wisdom is the daily bread of a managerial civilization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Doubter's Companion: A Dictionary of Aggressive Common Sense |id={{ASIN|0743236602|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n[[File:A stack of Economist papers.jpg|thumb|A stack of ''Economist'' papers, ordered by publication date. ''Pictured'': the 14 October 2019 issue. ]]\n''The Economist''{{'}}s primary focus is world events, politics and business, but it also runs regular sections on science and technology as well as books and the arts. Approximately every two weeks, the publication includes an in-depth special report<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/printedition/specialreports |title=Special reports |work=The Economist |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> (previously called [[survey article|surveys]]) on a given topic. The five main categories are Countries and Regions, Business, Finance and Economics, Science and Technology, and Other. Every three months, it publishes a technology report called ''Technology Quarterly''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/science/tq/ |title=Technology Quarterly |work=The Economist |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> or TQ, a special section focusing on recent trends and developments in science and technology.\n\nSince July 2007, there has also been a complete audio edition of the paper available 9&nbsp;pm London time on Thursdays.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Katie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/11/pressandpublishing.business1 |title=Economist launches audio magazine|work=The Guardian|location=London |date=11 July 2007 |accessdate=21 September 2016 }}</ref> The audio version of ''The Economist'' is produced by the production company ''Talking Issues''. The company records the full text of the newspaper in [[MP3]] format, including the extra pages in the UK edition. The weekly 130 MB download is free for subscribers and available for a fee for non-subscribers.\n\nThe publication's writers adopt a tight style that seeks to include the maximum amount of information in a limited space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/research/StyleGuide/|title=The Economist style guide|accessdate=27 December 2006|work=The Economist }}</ref> [[David G. Bradley]], publisher of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', described the formula as \"a consistent world view expressed, consistently, in tight and engaging prose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp|title=A Seven Year Ambition|work=mediabistro.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010200210/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlDC/magazines/more_on_atlantic_medias_new_superstar_20765.asp |archivedate=10 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Letters===\n''The Economist'' frequently receives letters from senior businesspeople, politicians, ambassadors, and from spokespeople for various government departments, non-governmental organisations and lobbies. Well-written or witty responses from anyone are considered, and controversial issues frequently produce a torrent of letters. For example, the survey of [[corporate social responsibility]], published January 2005, produced largely critical letters from [[Oxfam]], the [[World Food Programme]], [[United Nations Global Compact]], the Chairman of [[BT Group]], an ex-Director of [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] and the UK [[Institute of Directors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-humanrights.org/Links/Repository/542754|title=Compilation: Full text of responses to Economist survey on Corporate Social Responsibility (January\u2013February 2005)|work=Business & Human Rights|accessdate=3 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nMany of the letters published are critical of its stance or commentary. After ''The Economist'' ran a critique of [[Amnesty International]] and human rights in general in its issue dated 24 March 2007, its letters page ran a reply from Amnesty, as well as several other letters in support of the organisation, including one from the head of the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=8954694|title=Letters: On Amnesty International and human rights, Iraq, tax breaks 4&nbsp;April 2007|date=4 April 2007|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 November 2007}}</ref> Rebuttals from officials within regimes such as the Singapore government are routinely printed, to comply with local [[right-of-reply]] laws without compromising editorial independence.<ref>{{cite book|author=Francis T. Seow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CnZjYJ3TduUC&pg=PA173|title=The Media Enthralled: Singapore Revisited|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|year=1998|isbn=9781555877798|pages=171\u2013175|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is extremely rare for any comment by ''The Economist'' to appear alongside any published letter. Letters published in the paper are typically between 150 and 200 words long (and began with the salutation \"Sir\" until the editorship of Zanny Minton Beddoes, the first female editor; they now have no salutation). Previous to a change in procedure, all responses to on-line articles were usually published in \"The Inbox\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/debate/theinbox/|title=Latest blog posts|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> Comments can now be made directly under each article.\n\n=== Columns ===\n[[File:Economist Cartoon.jpg|thumb|A [[political cartoon]] published by the newspaper in November 2010, depicting  the [[European debt crisis|2010 European sovereign debt crisis]].|alt=|253x253px]]\nThe publication runs several opinion columns whose names reflect their topic:<!--Bolded because these columns redirect here, per WP:BOLD.-->\n\n*'''''Babbage''''' (Technology): named for the inventor [[Charles Babbage]], this column was established in March 2010 and focuses on various technology related issues.\n*'''''Bagehot''''' (Britain): named for [[Walter Bagehot]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|t\n}}), 19th-century British constitutional expert and early editor of ''The Economist''. Since April 2017 it has been written by [[Adrian Wooldridge]], who succeeded [[David Rennie (columnist)|David Rennie]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Britain's cheering gloom|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21557752 |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Charlemagne moves town|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/charlemagne/2010/06/charlemagne_moves_town |work=The Economist |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''Banyan''''' (Asia): named for the [[banyan]] tree, this column was established in April 2009 and focuses on various issues across the Asian continent, and is written by [[Dominic Ziegler]].\n*'''''Baobab''''' (Africa & Middle East): named for the [[baobab]] tree, this column was established in July 2010 and focuses on various issues across the African continent.\n*'''''Bartleby''''' (Work and management): named after [[Bartleby|the titular character]] of a [[Herman Melville]] short story, this column was established in May 2018. It is written by [[Philip Coggan]].\n*'''''Bello''''' (Latin America): named for [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], a Venezuelan diplomat, poet, legislator and philosopher, who lived and worked in Chile.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Bello column: Choosing a Name|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/01/bello-column|work=The Economist|accessdate=25 March 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref> The column was established in January 2014 and is written by [[Michael Reid (journalist and writer)|Michael Reid]].\n*'''''Buttonwood''''' (Finance): named for the [[Platanus occidentalis|buttonwood]] tree where early [[Wall Street]] traders gathered. Until September 2006 this was available only as an on-line column, but it is now included in the print edition. Since 2018, it is written by John O'Sullivan, succeeding Philip Coggan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/john-osullivan/|title=John O'Sullivan|website=Economist|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n*'''''Chaguan''''' (China): named for Chaguan, the traditional Chinese Tea houses in [[Chengdu]], this column was established on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/09/13/the-economists-new-china-column-chaguan|publisher=The Economist website|title=The Economist's new China column: Chaguan|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n*'''''Charlemagne''''' (Europe): named for [[Charlemagne]], Emperor of the [[Francia|Frankish Empire]]. It is written by Jeremy Cliffe<ref>[http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ People: Jeremy Cliffe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075703/http://mediadirectory.economist.com/people/Jeremy-Cliffe/ |date=15 January 2019 }}{{snd}} Economist Media Directory. Retrieved 14/1/19</ref> and earlier it was written by David Rennie (2007\u20132010) and by Anton La Guardia<ref>{{cite news|title=Media Directory|url=https://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/anton-la-guardia|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 June 2012|date=9 June 2011}}</ref> (2010\u20132014).\n\n*'''''Erasmus''''' (Religion and public policy) \u2013 named after the Dutch [[Christian humanist]] [[Erasmus]].\n*'''''Game Theory''''' (Sport): named after [[Game theory|the science of predicting outcomes]] in a certain situation, this column focuses on \"sports major and minor\" and \"the politics, economics, science and statistics of the games we play and watch\".\n*'''''Johnson''''' (language): named for [[Samuel Johnson]], this column returned to the publication in 2016 and covers language. It is written by [[Robert Lane Greene]].\n*'''''Lexington''''' (United States): named for [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the site of the beginning of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. From June 2010 until May 2012 it was written by [[Peter David (journalist)|Peter David]], until his death in a car accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/lexington/2012/05/lexington|publisher=The Economist website|title=Lexington: Peter David|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n*'''''Prospero''''' (Books and arts): named after the character from [[William Shakespeare's]] play ''[[The Tempest]]'', this column reviews books and focuses on arts-related issues.\n*'''''Schumpeter''''' (Business): named for the economist [[Joseph Schumpeter]], this column was established in September 2009 and is written by Patrick Foulis.\n\n*'''''Free Exchange''''' (Economics): a general economics column, frequently based on academic research, replaced the column ''Economics Focus'' in January 2012\n*'''Obituary''' (recent death): Since 1997 it has been written by [[Ann Wroe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|title=An Interview with Ann Wroe, Obituaries Writer for The Economist|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223130322/http://thehairpin.com/2014/06/an-interview-with-ann-wroe-obituaries-writer-for-the-economist|archive-date=23 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper goes to press on Thursdays, between 6&nbsp;pm and 7&nbsp;pm GMT, and is available at newsagents in many countries the next day. It is printed at seven sites around the world. Known on their website as \"This week's print edition\", it is available online, albeit with only the first five viewed articles being free (and available to subscribers only mid-October 2009 \u2013 2010). ''The Economist'' also produces the annual ''The World in'' [''Year''] publication.\n===Innovation Awards===\n[[File:Dimitris Droutsas at The Economist conference.jpg|thumb|293x293px|Greek Foreign Minister [[Dimitrios Droutsas|Dimitris Droutsas]] speaking at 2011 Economist Conference. ]]\n''The Economist'' sponsors the yearly \"Economist Innovation Awards\", in the categories of bioscience, computing and communications, energy and the environment, social and economic innovation, business-process innovation, consumer products, and a special \"no boundaries\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|title=Economist Innovation Awards Categories|publisher=The Economist Group|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117061347/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/categories|archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref> The awards have been held since 2002. Nominations are held between 2 and 30 April. The award ceremony is then hosted on 15 November. Choices are based on the following factors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|title=Economist Innovation Awards Nomination Process|publisher=Economistconferences.co.uk|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507204053/http://www.economistconferences.co.uk/innovation/nominationprocess|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n* How much revenue their innovation has made their company or its economic impact on a specific good cause or society in general\n* The effect their work has had on the marketplace (or if it's created a whole new marketplace altogether)\n* The impact their innovation has had on a new type of science or technology\n\n===Writing competitions===\n''The Economist'' sponsors a wide-array of writing competitions and prices throughout the year for readers. In 1999, ''The Economist'' organised a global futurist writing competition, [[The World in 2050]]. Co-sponsored by [[Royal Dutch/Shell]], the competition included a first prize of [[United States dollar|US$]]20,000 and publication in ''The Economist''{{'}}s annual flagship publication, ''The World In''.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=20000422&id=01ZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2003,2039685 | title=What is your vision of the future? | work=New Straights Times | date=22 April 2000}}</ref> Over 3,000 entries from around the world were submitted via a website set up for the purpose and at various Royal Dutch Shell offices worldwide.<ref name=\"newstraightstimes2000\" /> The judging panel included [[Bill Emmott]], [[Esther Dyson]], Sir [[Mark Moody-Stuart]], and [[Matt Ridley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Getting better all the time |url=https://www.economist.com/node/16103826|work=The Economist |date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2019, they launched the Open Future writing competition with an inaugural youth essay-writing prompt about [[Global warming|climate change]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sefs.uw.edu/students/student-blog-post/climate-change-essay-contest-offered-by-the-economist/|title=Climate Change Essay Contest offered by The Economist|website=School of Environmental and Forest Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During this competition the paper accepted a submission from an [[Artificial intelligence|artificially-intelligent]] computer writing program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2019/10/4/20895836/ai-climate-change-economist-essay-contest-gpt2|title=The Economist\u2019s essay contest featured an AI submission. Here\u2019s what the judges thought.|last=Piper|first=Kelsey|date=2019-10-04|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Data journalism ==\n[[File:A_graphic_detail_of_The_Economist.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:A_graphic_detail_of_The_Economist.jpg|thumb|The paper launched a large [[data journalism]] platform in 2015, tasked with creating and developing [[Graphical model|graphical models]] for ''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] coverage.]]\nThe presence of [[data journalism]] in ''The Economist'' can be traced to its founding year in 1843. Initially, the weekly published basic [[international trade]] figures and tables.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/data-journalism-at-the-economist-gets-a-home-of-its-own-in-print-92e194c7f67e|title=Data journalism at The Economist gets a home of its own in print|last=Selby-Boothroyd|first=Alex|date=2018-10-18|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/read/newsletters/ama-with-the-economists-data-team|title=AMA with The Economist's data team - Newsletter|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The paper first included a graphical model in 1847, with a [[bubble chart]] detailing [[Precious metal|precious metals]], and its first [[Epistolary novel|non-epistolary chart]] was included in its 1854 issue, charting the [[Cholera|spread of cholera]].<ref name=\":02\" /> This early adoption of data-based articles was estimated to be \"a 100 years before [[Dot-com bubble|the field\u2019s modern emergence]]\" by ''Data Journalism.com.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/read/newsletters/ama-with-the-economists-data-team|title=AMA with The Economist's data team - Newsletter|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Its transition from [[broadsheet]] to [[magazine]]-style formatting led to the adoption of colored graphs, first in [[Fire engine red|fire-engine-red]] during the 1980s and then to a thematic blue in 2001.<ref name=\":02\" /> The ''Economist'' told their readers throughout the 2000s that the paper's editors had \"developed a taste for data-driven stories.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Starting in the late-2000s, they began to publish more and more articles that centered solely on charts, some of which began to be published daily.<ref name=\":02\" /> The daily charts are typically followed by a short, 300-word explanation.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/economist-using-12-person-data-journalism-team-drive-subscriptions/|title=How The Economist uses its 12-person data journalism team to drive subscriptions|date=2018-05-04|website=Digiday|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> In September 2009, ''The Economist''launched a [[Twitter]] account for their Data Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ECONdailycharts|title=The Economist Data Team (@ECONdailycharts) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the weekly formed a dedicated team of 12 [[Data analysis|data analysts]], designers, and journalists to head up their firm-wide data journalism efforts.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.economist.com/turning-a-page-the-economists-data-journalism-gets-its-own-place-in-print-664c2e5bdfe9|title=Turning a page: The Economist\u2019s data journalism gets its own place in print|last=Economist|first=The|date=2018-10-22|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In order to ensure transparency in their data collection ''The Economist'' maintains a corporate [[GitHub]] account to publicly disclosure all of their models and software.<ref name=\":2\" /> In October 2018, they introduced their \"Graphic Detail\" feature in both their print and digital editions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Graphic Detail feature would go on to include mainly graphs, maps, and [[Infographic|infographics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journalism.co.uk/news/the-economist-s-print-edition-launches-a-dedicated-data-journalism-page-for-better-visual-storytelling/s2/a729384/|title=The Economist's print edition launches a dedicated data journalism page for better visual storytelling {{!}} Media news|date=2018-10-23|website=www.journalism.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Just as they engage with readers through their letters to the editor scheme, they, too, ask readers to write in their suggestions about how data could be better represented.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''The Economist''<nowiki/>'s Data Team won the 2020 Sigma Data Journalism Award for Best Young Journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datajournalism.com/awards|title=Sigma Data Journalism Awards|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=DataJournalism.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020|quote=G. Elliott Morris, Organisation: The Economist (United States)}}</ref> In 2015, they placed third for an infographic describing [[Politics of Israel|Israel's coalition networks]] in the year's Data Journalism Awards by the [[Global Editors Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaleditorsnetwork.org/programmes/data-journalism-awards/dja-newsletter/|title=DJA Newsletter|last=|first=|date=|website=GEN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020|quote=To explain something complex doesn\u2019t always require an interactive graphic. This look by The Economist\u2019s  team illustrates the complexities of Israeli politics in one long chart where it pays to scroll \u2014 and which would work equally well in print as online.}}</ref>\n\n=== Indexes ===\nHistorically, the publication has also maintained a section of [[economic statistics]], such as employment figures, economic growth, and interest rates. These statistical publications have been found to be seen as authoritative and decisive in British society.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3WVLKKSOcGYC&pg=PA88|title=Great expectations\u2014the social sciences in Great Britain|publisher=Commission on the Social Sciences|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7658-0849-3|page=88}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also publishes a variety of rankings seeking to position [[Business school|business schools]] and and [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate universities]] among each other, respectively. In 2015, they publish their first ranking of U.S. universities, focusing on comparable economical advantages. Their data for the rankings is sourced from the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] and is calculated as a function of median earnings through [[regression analysis]].<ref>{{cite journal|date=29 October 2015|title=The Economist \"The value of university: Our first-ever college rankings\"|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2015/10/value-university|journal=The Economist|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> Among others, the most well-known [[Index (economics)|data indexes]] the weekly publishes are:<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n* The [[Big Mac Index]]: a measure of the [[Purchasing power parity|purchasing power]] of currencies, first published in 1986, using the price of the hamburger in different countries.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Paul R. Krugman, Maurice Obstfeld|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NZnk5C2r8qEC&pg=PA396|title=International Economics|publisher=Pearson Education|year=2009|isbn=978-0-321-55398-0|page=396}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=6\u201312 September 1986|title=On the Hamburger Standard|journal=The Economist}}</ref> This is published twice a year, annually.\n* The Glass Ceiling Index: a measure of [[Occupational sexism|female equality in the workplace]].\n* The Most Dangerous Cities Index: a measure of major cities [[List of countries by intentional homicide rate|by rates of homicide]].\n\n==Opinions==\n{{Main|The Economist editorial stance}}\n\nThe editorial stance of ''The Economist'' primarily revolves around [[classical liberalism|classical]] and [[economic liberalism]]. Since its founding, it has supported [[radical centrism]], favoring polices and governments that maintain [[Centrism|centrist politics]]. The newspaper favors [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal economics]], particularly [[Free market|free markets]], [[free trade]], [[free immigration]] and [[Globalization|globalisation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/17732859|title=Globalisation: The redistribution of hope|date=16 December 2010|work=The Economist|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref> When the newspaper was founded, the term \"[[economism]]\" denoted what would today be termed \"[[economic liberalism]]\". The activist and journalist [[George Monbiot]] has described it as [[neoliberalism|neo-liberal]] while occasionally accepting the propositions of [[Keynesian economics]] where deemed more \"reasonable\".<ref name=\"Grauniad\">{{cite news|author=George Monbiot|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/jan/11/economy.g8|title=George Monbiot, Punitive \u2013 and it works|date=11 January 2005|work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 May 2012|location=London}}</ref> The weekly favours a [[carbon tax]] to fight [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite journal|date=14 June 2008|title=Buttonwood: Let them heat coke|url=https://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11543656|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> According to one former editor, Bill Emmott, \"the ''Economist''{{'}}s philosophy has always been liberal, not conservative\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Emmot|first=Bill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/monarchy/story/0,2763,408484,00.html|title=Time for a referendum on the monarchy|date=8 December 2000|work=Comment|accessdate=27 December 2006|location=London}}</ref> [[File:David Hume and Adam Smith statues.jpg|thumb|Scottish economist [[Adam Smith]] (''right'') and philosopher [[David Hume]] (''left'') represent the newspaper's foundational beliefs of ''[[laissez-faire]]'' [[Economic policy|policies]], [[self-sufficiency]], [[Protectionism|anti-protectionism]] and [[free trade]].|alt=]]Individual contributors take diverse views. ''The Economist'' favours the support, through [[central bank]]s, of banks and other important corporations. This principle can, in a much more limited form, be traced back to [[Walter Bagehot]], the third editor of ''The Economist'', who argued that the Bank of England should support major banks that got into difficulties. [[Karl Marx]] deemed ''The Economist'' the \"European organ\" of \"the aristocracy of finance\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Marx|first=Karl|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1852/18th-brumaire/ch06.htm|title=The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte|year=1852}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper has also supported liberal causes on social issues such as recognition of gay marriages,<ref>[https://www.economist.com/PrinterFriendly.cfm?story_id=2515389 Let them wed], cover article on 4 January 1996</ref> legalisation of drugs,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100602002643/http://www.drogasedemocracia.org/Arquivos/the-economist.pdf How to stop the drug wars], cover article on 7 March 2009.  The publication calls legalisation \"the least bad solution\".</ref> criticises the [[Taxation in the United States|US tax model]],<ref>{{cite journal|date=4 February 2012|title=Tax reform in America: A simple bare necessity|url=https://www.economist.com/node/21545981|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> and seems to support some government regulation on health issues, such as smoking in public,<ref>{{cite journal|date=10 June 2010|title=Smoking and public health: Breathe easy|url=https://www.economist.com/node/16333351|journal=The Economist|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> as well as bans on spanking children.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11455006 \"Spare The Rod, Say Some\"], ''The Economist'', 31 May 2008.</ref> ''The Economist'' consistently favours guest worker programmes, parental choice of school, and amnesties<ref>[https://www.economist.com/opinion/displayStory.cfm?story_id=6744217 Sense, not Sensenbrenner], The Economist, 30 March 2006</ref> and once published an \"obituary\" of God.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/obituary/1999/12/23/god|title=Obituary: God|date=23 December 1999|work=The Economist|access-date=}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also has a long record of supporting gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/node/13447986|title=Lexington: Reflections on Virginia Tech|date=8 April 2009|work=The Economist|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' has endorsed the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (in 2005), the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] (in 2010 and 2015),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/29/the-economist-backs-conservatives \"The Economist backs the Conservatives\"], ''The Guardian'' (PA report), 29 April 2010.</ref><ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite journal|date=2 May 2015|title=Who should govern Britain?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21650113-despite-risk-europe-coalition-led-david-cameron-should-have-second-term-who|journal=The Economist|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref> and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (in 2017 and 2019) at general election time in Britain, and both [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidates in the United States. ''Economist.com'' puts its stance this way:\n\n{{quotation|What, besides free trade and free markets, does ''The Economist'' believe in? \"It is to the Radicals that ''The Economist'' still likes to think of itself as belonging. The extreme centre is the paper's historical position\". That is as true today as when Crowther [Geoffrey, ''Economist'' editor 1938\u20131956] said it in 1955. ''The Economist'' considers itself the enemy of privilege, pomposity and predictability. It has backed conservatives such as [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Margaret Thatcher]]. It has supported the Americans in [[Vietnam]]. But it has also endorsed [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Bill Clinton]], and espoused a variety of liberal causes: opposing capital punishment from its earliest days, while favouring penal reform and decolonisation, as well as\u2014more recently\u2014gun control and gay marriage.<ref name=\"About us\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/help/about-us#About_The_Economist|title=About us|accessdate=21 September 2016|work=The Economist|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>}}\n''The Economist'' frequently accuses figures and countries of corruption or dishonesty. In recent years, for example, it criticised [[Paul Wolfowitz]], [[World Bank]] president; [[Silvio Berlusconi]], Italy's Prime Minister (who dubbed it ''The Ecommunist'');<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2005/09/324682.html|title=Report of Rome anti-war demo on Saturday 24th with photos|work=[[Independent Media Center]]|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila]], the late president of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]; [[Robert Mugabe]], the former head of government in [[Zimbabwe]]; and, recently, [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]], the president of Argentina.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/la/displaystory.cfm?story_id=11293743|title=Cristina in the land of make believe|date=1 May 2008|work=The Economist}}</ref> ''The Economist'' also called for [[impeachment of Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton's impeachment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/1998/09/17/just-go|title=Just go|date=1998-09-17|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> and, after the emergence of the [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=2647493|title=Resign Rumsfeld|date=6 May 2004|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> for [[Donald Rumsfeld]]'s resignation. Though ''The Economist'' initially gave vigorous support for the [[Iraq War|US-led invasion of Iraq]], it later called the operation \"bungled from the start\" and criticised the \"almost criminal negligence\" of the Bush Administration's handling of the war, while maintaining, in 2007, that pulling out in the short term would be irresponsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/world/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_RRRTGGP|title=Mugged by reality|date=22 March 2007|work=The Economist|accessdate=9 April 2007}}</ref> In the 2004 US election, the editors \"reluctantly\" backed John Kerry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?story_id=E1_QTVPPQ|title=Crunch time in America|date=2 November 2000|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=3329802|title=The incompetent or the incoherent?|date=28 October 2004|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref> In the 2008 US election ''The Economist'' endorsed [[Barack Obama]], while using the front cover of the issue published on the eve of the election to promote his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/opinion/displaystory.cfm?source=most_commented&story_id=12511171|title=It's time|date=30 October 2008|work=The Economist}}</ref> In the 2012 US election, Barack Obama was again endorsed: the editorial said that they preferred Obama on the economy, foreign policy and health care, but criticised him for running a negative campaign against Romney and for a \"...poor appreciation of commerce.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21565623-america-could-do-better-barack-obama-sadly-mitt-romney-does-not-fit-bill-which-one?spc=scode&spv=xm&ah=9d7f7ab945510a56fa6d37c30b6f1709|title=Our American Endorsement. Which one?|date=3 November 2012|newspaper=The Economist|accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the Economist endorse [[Hillary Clinton]], and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] due \"[p]artly because she is not Mr Trump, but also in the hope she can show that ordinary politics works for ordinary people\u2014the sort of renewal that American democracy requires.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2016/11/05/americas-best-hope|title=America's best hope|date=2016-11-05|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-08-27|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nIn an editorial marking its 175th anniversary, ''The Economist'' criticised adherents to liberalism for becoming too inclined to protect the political status quo rather than pursue reform.<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/essay/2018/09/13/the-economist-at-175|title=The Economist at 175|date=13 September 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>{{Non-primary source needed|date=May 2019}} The paper called on liberals to return to advocating for bold political, economic and social reforms: protecting [[free market]]s, land and tax reform in the tradition of [[Georgism]], [[open immigration]], a rethink of the [[social contract]] with more emphasis on education, and a revival of [[liberal internationalism]].<ref name=\"The Economist at 175\" />\n\n==Circulation==\n[[File:The Economist Display.jpg|thumb|A display of newspapers in [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]] supermarket, depicting the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\nEach of ''The Economist'' issue's official date range is from Saturday to the following Friday. ''The Economist'' posts each week's new content online at approximately 2100 Thursday evening UK time, ahead of the official publication date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/babbage/2011/08/service-announcement|title=The Economist launches on Android|date=2 August 2011|work=The Economist|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> From July to December 2019, their average global [[Circulation (journal)|print circulation]] was over 909,476, while combined with their digital presence, runs to over 1.6 million.<ref name=\"pgazette\" /> However, on a weekly average basis, the paper can reach up to 5.1 million readers, across their print and digital runs.<ref name=\"pgazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/seriously-popular-economist-now-claims-reach-53m-readers-week-print-and-online|title=Seriously popular: The Economist now claims to reach 5.3m readers a week in print and online|publisher=pressgazette.co.uk|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> Across their social media platforms, it reaches an audience of 35 million, as of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/economist-boasts-15m-magazine-circulation-and-36m-social-media-followers/|title=The Economist boasts 1.5m magazine circulation and 36m social media followers|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date=March 8, 2016|website=Press Gazette|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1877, the publication's circulation was 3,700, and in 1920 it had risen to 6,000. Circulation increased rapidly after 1945, reaching 100,000 by 1970.<ref name=\"About us\" /> Circulation is audited by the [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]] (ABC). From around 30,000 in 1960 it has risen to near 1 million by 2000 and by 2016 to about 1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Lucinda Southern|date=17 February 2016|title=The Economist Plans to Double Circulation Profits in 5 Years|url=http://digiday.com/publishers/economist-aims-double-circulation-profits-5-years/|magazine=[[Digiday]]|access-date=7 July 2016}}</ref> Sales inside North America were in 2007 around 54 per cent of the total, with sales in the UK making up 14 per cent of the total and continental Europe 19 per cent. ''The Economist'' claims sales, both by subscription and at newsagents, in over 200 countries. Of its American readers, two out of three earn more than $100,000 a year.<ref name=\"gainsreaders\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5250996|title='Economist' Magazine Wins American Readers|date=8 March 2006|publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]]|accessdate=27 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' once boasted about its limited circulation. In the early 1990s it used the slogan \"''The Economist'' \u2013 not read by millions of people\". \"Never in the history of journalism has so much been read for so long by so few,\" wrote [[Geoffrey Crowther, Baron Crowther|Geoffrey Crowther]], a former editor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moseley|first=Ray|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D3B56996BE43&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=\"Economist\" aspires to influence, and many say it does.|work=The Chicago Tribune|accessdate=14 May 2008|format=pay archive}}</ref>\n\nThe Economist Newspaper Limited is a wholly owned subsidiary of [[The Economist Group]]. The publications of the group include the ''CFO'' brand family as well as the annual ''The World in...'', and the bimonthly [[lifestyle magazine]], ''[[1843 (magazine)|1843]].'' Sir [[Evelyn Robert de Rothschild]] was Chairman of the company from 1972 to 1989.\n\n==Censorship==\n[[File:A page ripped out from The Economist by China's censorship department (cropped).jpg|thumb|232x232px|A page ripped out from ''The Economist'' by China's censorship department in [[Liaoning Provincial Museum|Liaoning Provincial Library]]. ]]\nSections of ''The Economist'' criticising authoritarian regimes are frequently removed from the paper by the authorities in those countries. ''The Economist'' regularly has difficulties with the ruling party of Singapore, the [[People's Action Party]], which had successfully sued it, in a Singaporean court, for [[Defamation|libel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Southeast_Asia/HL01Ae01.html|title=Inconvenient truths in Singapore|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[Asia Times]] }}</ref>\n\nLike many other publications, ''The Economist'' is subjected to censorship in [[India]] whenever it depicts a map of [[Kashmir]]. The maps are stamped by Indian Customs officials as being \"neither correct, nor authentic\". Issues are sometimes delayed, but not stopped or seized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/12/censorship_india|title=Censorship in India|work=The Economist | date=7 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, [[Iran]] banned the sale of ''The Economist'' when it published a map labelling the [[Persian Gulf]] simply as Gulf\u2014a choice that derives its political significance from the [[Persian Gulf naming dispute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1150191582529&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Iran bans ''The Economist'' over map|accessdate=31 January 2007|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] }}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, the government of [[Zimbabwe]] went further and imprisoned ''The Economist''{{'}}s correspondent there, [[Andrew Meldrum]]. The government charged him with violating a statute on \"publishing untruth\" for writing that a woman was decapitated by supporters of the ruling [[Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Patriotic Front]] party. The [[decapitation]] claim was retracted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |title=Guardian and RFI correspondent risks two years in jail |accessdate=2 April 2014 |work=[[Reporters Without Borders]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404211952/http://www.rsf.org/article.php3?id_article=2574 |archivedate=4 April 2009 }}</ref> and allegedly fabricated by the woman's husband. The correspondent was later acquitted, only to receive a [[deportation]] order.\n\nOn 19 August 2013, ''The Economist'' disclosed that the Missouri Department of Corrections had censored its issue of 29 June 2013. According to the letter sent by the department, prisoners were not allowed to receive the issue because \"1. it constitutes a threat to the security or discipline of the institution; 2. may facilitate or encourage criminal activity; or 3. may interfere with the rehabilitation of an offender\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist in prison: About that missing issue|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2013/08/economist-prison|work=The Economist|accessdate=2 April 2014|date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of business newspapers]]\n* [[List of newspapers in the United Kingdom]]\n{{Portal bar|Journalism|Media|Business|News|United Kingdom|Europe}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Arrese, Angel (1995), ''La identidad de The Economist,'' Pamplona: Eunsa. {{ISBN|9788431313739}}. ([https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326415042_La_identidad_de_The_Economist preview])\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.thebalancesmb.com/best-business-magazines-4176680|title=The 8 Best Business Magazines of 2020|last=Delbridge|first=Emily|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Balance Small Business|publisher=Dotdash|location=New York City|page=|pages=|at=Best Economics Reporting: The Economist|doi=|pmid=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 Feb 2020|magazine=}}\n* Edwards, Ruth Dudley (1993), ''The Pursuit of Reason: The Economist 1843\u20131993'', London: Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-12939-7}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Media Monoliths|author=Tungate|first=Mark|location=|pages=194\u2013206|chapter=''The Economist''|publisher=Kogan Page Publishers|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7494-4108-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|The_Economist.ogg|12 July 2006}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.economist.com/}}\n* {{HathiTrust Catalog}}\n\n{{Rothschilds}}\n{{The Economist Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economist, The}}\n\n<!--Do not add any categories about newsmagazine or magazines, The Economist is a newspaper, printed in magazine-format.-->\n[[Category:The Economist]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:International newspapers]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Business newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Websites utilizing paywalls]]\n", "name_user": "DonSpencer1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eData journalism:rv. broke cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Economist"}
